Location: Slash Boulder > Western Belt > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Another of Joshua Tree's finest boulder problems, this ascends the center of a beautiful vertical face peppered with juggy slashes. The crux is encountered fairly low on the problem, leaving many airy jugs to be savored. The problem tops out at around 25 ft. with an easy, yet committing mantel.
,
This fairly obvious boulder is located along the approach to Jerry's Quarry. Park at turnout #5 (on the right, just before the Road Unmaintained sign), walk west towards the largest formation (Jerry's Quarry) for approximately 1/2 mile to a large boulder that sits next to a small rockpile, just before a very large wash. The problem is on the west side of the boulder.
,
Pads, Spotters

Location: JBMF Boulder > JBMF Boulders > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

This classic problem takes a proud line directly up the middle of the large boulder near False Up 20 (V0-), and sits directly across the road from Double Cross.

Â Depending on how tall you are there are a few different starting holds, but thin holds are the name of the game on this problem.Â 

Don't breath too hard as you might blow yourself off the crux, but as you hit that last hold with your right hand, rest assured that the final throw for the lip might look far but that hold is huge!

,
You will want 2 pads if you are working this by yourself. If not, 1 pad and a good spotter will do. It's probably about 15' high.

Location: Gunsmoke Wall > Gunsmoke Area > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Classic. Like Yosemite's Midnight Lightning, Hueco Tank's Ghetto Simulator or Boulder's Monkey Traverse, Gunsmoke requires little introduction.

The Gunsmoke Traverse is L-shaped and is usually done from left to right. Start as far left as possible, move right along the wall for about 50' past 2 crux sections, turn the corner (third crux), and continue another 35' along rails to a final bulge. If your guns aren't too smoked, reverse your moves back to the start.

GUNSMOKE IS LIKELY THE SINGLE MOST CROWDED ROUTE IN THE PARK, and it's not uncommon to find a dozen or more people there at any given time. Several other quality problems can be found in the vicinity, including the classic stemming problem Streetcar Named Desire (V6) and The Chube (V2). Southern exposure makes this a hot one during mid-day - best done in the late afternoon.
,
Crash pad.
,

Location: Stem Gem Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located in a small group of campsites on the Southern end of the Blob formation. Please ask permission for bouldering in occupied campsites.

Stem Gem is the Quintessencial JTree boulder problem, embodying the essence of Joshua Tree climbing: Highly technical and often times perplexing movement across extremely friction dependant, featurless granite. Indeed, this problem has nary a hold on it, the only thing making it climbable is its coarse friction and the undulating nature of the stone.

Getting both feet off the ground on this problem can be an event in itself, bringing ones flexability and stemming prowess to task. Start by stemming up the concave face and then traversing right across a faint/blunt arete. Most continue right and stand on the "bump", however it is possible to avoid the bump and friction direct (v3 friction in itself), continue up the water groove and to the top of the boulder. Jump across boulder to get off.
,
standard bouldering gear
]

Downclimb the juggy crack just right to descend.
,
Up the center of the boulder and about 5' left of Spud Crack.

Sit your butt in the dirt on all the very chalked up holds about 3/4 of the way left of the wall. Use whichever holds you like and can reach from the ground. From here, traverse right on weird huecos & xenoliths until you get to some tension-y underclongs and a long reach for a shoulder. Figure out hot to get firmly into this shoulder and then bust out high & right for a juggy crack system. Take the juggy crack system up & then either drop off at the top jugs or pull the sketchy top out moves if you feel like it.

This boulder is a lone boulder in the outback. 34.02174, -116.16332

Location: Caveman Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start by climbing an adjacent boulder on the right side of the cave to access the huge starting jugs, traverse left on STEEEP jugs with bad feet to a cruXy low spot in the roof, finishing up fins and jugs. Downclimb and step off to finish at either the highest jug or at the furthest jug to the left.

Traversing high at the start and utilizing the "hidden" hold, this problem might be V6, traversing low at the start is probably more like V7, avoiding the "hidden" hold is even a bit harder (IMO more esthetic). I think this problem deserves AT LEAST 1 star, prolly 2 because of the uniqueness of the climbing involved.

The sit starts low on the far right of the cave at a pinch and a sloping undercling, about 10 feet below the regular start. Crumbly starting holds have made this start harder over the years. Consensus is that it is a fairly solid V10, holding on for nearly 25 moves being the business.
,
pad
]

Location: Betty Jo Rock > Entrance Boulder & Vicinity > Real Hidden Valley Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
One of 10 or so classic high balls in the Park, as well as one of the easiest, this is the first climbable feature you'll see on your left as you enter the real Hidden valley corridor. Refrain from setting a TR and just go for it as the crux is encountered midway while leaving the top is a feeling to be savored and not feared.

Don't expect to send in a quiet setting as foot traffic is heavy here. That's ok though, more people to hoot as you top out!
,
On a small, east-facing wall 75' west of and facing the Entrance Boulder, and right off the trail leading into Real Hidden Valley.
,
A pad (more is nicer)
]

,
From Manx Boulders walk toward main park road. "The Womb" boulder is to your right about 1/4 of a mile, near the main rocks. "The Womb" is on the far side of the boulder. This is visible, but a bit hard to discern, from the road.

Location: Manx Boulders - Northwest Face > Manx Boulders > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
A fun problem that is a good bit easier for tall people. Make a long move to a crimp, step up onto a bad foot and grab the undercling. Mantle over the top on good slopers. For short people, getting the undercling will likely be the crux, for taller people the topout.
,
Just left of Undertow, going to an obvious undercling flake about 8ft off the ground. Descend by chimneying down between the two boulders.
,
Pad.
]

Location: Chuckawalla Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This short but sweet problem is located on the north face of the eponymous Chuckawalla Boulder which is located very near the infamous Iron Door Cave.

A series of balancy liebacks are the heart of this problem which offers fun and balancy movement throughout it's length. The movement on this problem is reminiscent of the Fry Problem near Cap Rock.

A sit start (V6) exists to this problem which powers left into the normal start via slopers, gastons and liebacks making this problem nearly twice as long.
,
pad

Location: Gunsmoke Wall > Gunsmoke Area > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

Climb juggy rails up to a vertical crack with a big move to the sloping lip. An easy mantel gets you onto the ledge, ending the problem. Walk off the ramp to the left.
,
A pad may be desirable as the ground is hard packed dirt.

Location: Streetcar Boulder > Gunsmoke Area > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

The run-n-jump is prolly V5

A pad is nice, hard dirt.

Description:
[
Climb sidepulls and thin ledges to a horizontal rail about 3/4 up. From here, the crux requires a left gaston on a small crystal and some balance. Exit up and right.

From the Hall of Horrors parking lot, take the trail along the right side of the formations. You will pass the two main formations (East Wall, then West Wall). A larger section of desert separates the West Wall from King Dome. Cross this and head to the NE corner of Kingdome. There is one, very large boulder located on this corner. LHMFP is the only climb located on the SW face (other climbs are located on the NW, and NE faces).

pads and a spotter. sandy landing but with a few yucca nearby.

This fun and somwhat unique problem is found on the west face of the boulder just left of center.
,
pad
]

Location: Fidelman Boulder > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This climbs the undercut arete on the south end of the boulder.
,
Pad.
]

Location: Chuckawalla Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This short but fun dyno/reach problem is located just right of Chuckawalla (V1) on the far right side of the Chuckawalla Boulder.

This somewhat height-dependent problem starts with both hands matched on a large flat rail and involves a dyno or long reach to the incut jugs at the lip - kinda like going for the top of a fence. An easy descent exists off the northeast corner of the boulder.

A fun variation (V1) to this problem it to SDS with hands matched on the large flake/jug just to the left and work up to the rail and then work up small edges before grabbing the lip.
,
pad
]

Location: Cap Rock > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This Crack is about 30 ft. (IÂ’ll go back and check) to the right of High Heeled Sneakers. A nice, slippery, 5.8 thin crack. Walk off left.
,
Pad.
]

Location: Wedge Boulder > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
The crux comes right off the deck, and once you're started it's a bit of a stroll to the top, that is if slab climbing is your specialty. The start is a few feet right of the left arete.
,
This problem is on the Wedge boulder which is by So High. Downclimb the backside to get down.
,
Pads
]

Location: Dream Sequence Boulder > Lonely Stones > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start and compress the double aretes, climbing up and left following the lip of the boulder, ending at a large dish above the overhang, then mantel.
,
From the approach, the problem is on the backside (east side) of the boulder.
,
pad
]

Location: Pinhead Boulder > HVCG North > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start just right of Pinhead at the obvious chunky dike and climb up and right on mostly good holds to finish on a ledge below the top of the boulder - continue traversing right to the backside to descend. Probably about 5.8 or so in difficulty and done from a sit start is only slightly harder (5.9).
,
Right side of West Face and just right of Pinhead.
,
pad
]

Location: Pinhead Boulder > HVCG North > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start left of Pinhead and climb the off-vertical face with a delicate and semi-comitting crux move near the top.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
West face of boulder and just left of Pinhead.
,
Pad
]

Location: Voices Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Fun moves up a featured arete (5.7) splashed with patina is the name of the game, but unfortunately it's over all too soon. This problem is a good introduction to bouldering in general and perfectly suited as a warmup for the more difficult problems nearby.

A sit start can be done and is slighty harder (about 5.9 or so) in difficulty and adds a few more quality moves.
,
Located on the on the west face of the Voices Boulder and just left of Voices Arete which is on the opposite arete.
,
pad
]

Location: Chocolate Boulder 1 > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Stand start at the southwest corner of the boulder with hands matched on a large incut jug.

Â Traverse out left via an overhanging rail that requires some creative footwork and reaches and finish up the arete on the same side of the boulder.

  • An easier finish (~V3) turns the arete to the left and ends on a slab.
,

Pad and maybe a spotter to keep you off a rock at the crux.

]

Location: Trashcan Boulders > Trashcan Rock Area > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Fun easy traverse. Can do a sit start but all in all its just fun movement on stone, its located on the front of trash can rock (facing the road). Start left and the further right you go the harder it gets.
,
Maybe a spotter
]

Location: Planet X Boulder > Planet X Area > Planet X Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
One of the all time great dyno problems. Considered by many to be the best boulder problem in JTree. Start off a large cheatstone (although not necessary), climb jugs up to a blank, vertical headwall with thin crimps, to an all out dyno for a huge jug 20 ft. off the deck. Finishes with a few mildly exciting sloper moves.
,
bring large nuts!
]

Location: Sandy Wash Corridor > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
The left side of the face, climb obvious small crimps up overhanging rock of excellent quality. At the higher horizontal somewhat larger crimps provide a bit of relief as you figure out how to negotiate the completely blank, rounded topout and get to that jug that's too far away :) Totally awesome problems and reasonably straightforward for the grade compared to some of Joshua Tree's classic "blank" nightmares!
,
Pad. A bit high - you face a 10-12 foot fall at the crux, make sure you have a good spot and/or don't miss your pad.
]

Location: Manx Boulders - Northwest Face > Manx Boulders > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb up and gain the left slanting rail. From here reach up to the dish and finish out on slopers.
,
Just to the right of the central break.
,
Pads
]

Location: Caveman Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start at the lowest point of the roof finish on Caveman V6-7, then climb toward the entrance on huecos, fins, and pinches. Finish at any highpoint.
,
Pads
]

Location: Lizzie Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start on the jug rail at the bottom of the face in the middle of the overhang/roof. Make huge move to small 3 finger crimp, then to a gaston, and to a jug.

,
crash pads and a spotter
]

Location: Wedge Boulder > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Follow the Northwest (i.e. left-hand) arete up to the top. The route is not tricky, but keeping your head together for this moderate high ball is.

Start at the bomber sloper just around the corner for a satisfying lie-back. Stay on main face, or pass over the arete and climb the north face.

Climb down on back of boulder is a bit easier, especially if you follow the arete on the Southeast side, which has great hands.
,
At main face of boulder, look to left-hand side arrete. Boulder is very visible from trail, and comes just before Wave and So High boulders.
,
Multiple pads if possible.
]

Location: Scatterbrain Boulder > Scatterbrain Area > HVCG North > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start from a high incut edge and slap, pinch and heel hook your way up the overhung arete to a finishing jug - classic.

A sit start has been done at around V11.

,
Northeast arete of the boulder
,
Pad(s), spotter
]

Location: Triangle Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Slightly overhanging pulls on sizeable edges lead to a crux move to reach a large hold - shorter climbers may be at a disadvantage here. Run the feet up and mantle your way to the top.Â 

  • The downclimb is off the backside and stays very near the arete.
,

Located on the left side of the west face of the Triangle Boulder which is situated roughly midway between Caveman and Stem Gem.

,
pad
]

Location: Picture Perfect Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located just west of the Black Lichen Boulder on a small boulder which is tucked into a nest of other boulders.

Stand start at a high pinch on the arete, feet up on high edges and lock off/throw for an obvious jug. Once on the jug pull around onto the right side of the arete and surf grainy jugs to the top. Descend by jumping off onto an adjacent boulder.

A great problem for the grade with great rock and asthetic moves (the sit start is V5).
,
pad
]

Location: Igneous Boulder > Echo Cove Bouldering > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start at the two horns, climb the right side of the arÃªte.
,
Pads
]

Location: Collieherb Boulder > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Move up a vertical face on positive horizontal slashes. For the first couple moves, do what you can with thin, undercut feet. Good warmup, or a fun problem for those who (like me) prefer their boulders a bit easier than V6.

Park at the Cap Rock parking area and head up the left (north) fork of the nature trail. Collieherb will be just off to your right before the trail curves around the large rock formation; on the NW face, so you'll basically be staring right at it.
,
Nice clean landing. Pad might be nice, spotter probably not necessary
]

Location: Inquisition Bloc > Lonesome Crowded West > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start 10 feet under roof In wide crack, Climb the flaring offwidth to the top
,
On the inquisition block below the Rusty wall
,
Boulder, couple pads
]

Location: Yardarm Boulder > JBMF Boulders > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
far left boulder in the circuit behind Yabo Roof. right of Pig F**ker, horizontal slot high and left. short problem.
,
pad
]

Location: Roof Boulder > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Sit start deep in low roof on juggy incut with minimal feet. Fall's back into cruxy overhanging crack, easing out into juggy flake system to a big throw out and over the boulder to huge jug and an easy mantle top out.

Taller people will have a hard time dabbing on pads due to low clearance from roof to floor.

,

Directly behind Ryan Campground site 29, on top of the rock formation.

,
A couple of pads and a spotter
]

Location: Pumping Monzonite Boulder > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start with left hand on the sloper and right on the large undercling. Â Work up and right using varying techniques to gain the upper crack.

Original start was done off of a stone or stacked pad with right hand on the shark tooth crimp and left on a small seam crack.

,
About midway on the nature trail.
,
pad, spotters
]

Location: The Real Hall of Horrors > Hall of Horrors Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Traverse the juggy rail with the crux being a thin spot or two near the right side. Can be done in either direction and is conducive to doing laps if so inclined.
,
Located on the left (west) side of the corridor near the entrance.
,
pad
]

Location: Piano Rock > Gunsmoke Area > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This is the crack in the center of the West Face. Itï¿½s about 5.8 and gets juggy near the top.
,
Pad.
]

Location: The Blockhead > JBMF Boulders > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
start on the big triangle hold. good feet. throw high and right to a good hold. slap over the top and grovel for a top out
,
in between Yabo Roof and False Up 20 boulder. walk between the two medium sized boulders
,
pad
]

Location: Pigpen Boulder > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start as for Pigpen. From the bucket rest bust out to the arete and power up pinches and slopers to the lip and throw out left to a good hold. Top out on some slopey goodness.

,
Pigpen Boulder.
,
Pads
]

Location: Manx Boulders - Northwest Face > Manx Boulders > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This problem lies on the north face of the Manx Boulder directly behind a dying tree. Start at the obvious sloping ledge and make a big move to gain the lip, then press out a mantel with tree branches at your back (a little scary) to complete the problem.

UPDATE: Tree gone since 2007 or so.
,
Spotters and one or more crashpads.
]

Location: Land of the Lost Boulder > Echo Cove Bouldering > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
SDS lower left on edge rail, work right along seam/crack to join chorizo taco stand then finish on that route.
,
Left side of boulder
,
Pad
]

Location: Voices Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located on the west face of the Voices Boulder and just left of Scissorlock (V1) on a right-slanting arete.

Make some off-balance moves to get established on the bouldder and then work the featured arete to the top. The start is a bit tricky for the grade (5.9) but the landing is nice and flat which encourages one to go for it.
,
pad
]

Location: Master Cylinder > Echo Rock Boulders > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Match start on the low rail, power up and then left on tricky slopers to the arete. Finish up the smooth tall slab. Sandy flat landing.
,
Right most climb. In between the two boulders, near the crack.
,
Pads and spotters.
]

Location: Moffat Boulder > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Chili Sauce is a fairly obvious dihedral on a boulder that lies near the right side of the formation on the desert floor.

Climb a short, overhanging dihedral with sweet diagonal rails and stems. Move out left to a pockety seam and a diamond shaped black diorite edge. Power through the crimpy crux to a jug over the top.
,
A pad is nice to cover a rock underneath the crux.
]

Location: Pinhead Boulder > HVCG North > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb up the left edge of the face that Pinhead is on, using the arete.
,
pad
]

Location: X-Men Boulder > The Hang > Planet X Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
starts on large pinch 6ft up, move up and left on diagonal cracks to thin edges and a grainy arete
,
pads
]

Location: Nixon Cracks > HVCG North > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
A beautiful hands/off-hands crack on a vertical face with a small overhang at the top.
,
The left boulder length crack when looking at Nixon cracks.
,
pads
]

Location: Feature Boulder (aka Fred Nicole Boulder) > Inner Circle > The Underground > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start at the bottom, go up and traverse right along cool patina to the top.
,
pads
]

Location: The Iron Meteorite (aka Kingpin Boulder) > King Dome Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Climb juggy patina plates and edges up a bulging face to about two-thirds height where the rock changes color and the holds get much smaller and worse.Â 

Work your feet up as high as possible as you hold onto sloping grains and aim for a visible depression at the lip.Â 

Downclimb off the backside.

,
Center of the west face of the boulder.
,

Pads, spottersÂ 

]

Location: False Up 20 Boulder > JBMF Boulders > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This nice crack is on the west-side of the boulder. It is actually the right-side of the False Up 20 flake and obviously lies to the right of "False Up 20".
You may want to climb up it before descending it.It's about 5.7.
,
Pad and spotter if you wish.
]

Location: Blas Beemer Boulder > Blas Beemer Area > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb the prominent, left leaning thin crack and pockets on the west face above a low cave.
,
pad
]

Location: The Blockhead > JBMF Boulders > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start to False Blockhead. Start on the low crimps.
,
Pads
]

Location: The Rosetta Stone > Loveland Bouldering > Pinto Basin (aka Eastern Territorries) > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Yet another of Joshua Trees most beautiful boulder problems, Alexandria, which follows a crescent shaped Aplite dike of superb quality, and ascends a dead vertical face that rises 23 ft., climbing nearly 20 ft. of absolutely perfect edges.

Jump start to a 1 inch deep rail that is about 9ft. up, above a cave-like area. Angle around left and up on immaculate tile smooth rails, up to a royal crown of Jugs. The start has also been done static, pulling off razor thin crimps, done this way it is V9.

This problem, as well as the others on this boulder were all FA'd ground up, no pre-inspection, no pre-cleaning.
,
May need several pads to reach start.
]

Location: Intersection Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This boulder is located on the east side of Intersection Rock (hence the name) and sits out away from the formation with another smaller rock next to it (the smaller rock has a worthwhile 5.9 mantle on the east side). There are three problems on this face - the left one is V1, the middle one is V2 and the right one is V3. They are all kinda sketchy, so make sure you have some spotters and some pads.
,
spotters, pads
]

Location: Xenolithic Boulder > Loveland Bouldering > Pinto Basin (aka Eastern Territorries) > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climbs a stunning black, overhanging arete with big moves between slick slopers and a "psych" topout. Fire through big triangular slopers, up and left to a rail and a juggy flake. Commit to the psyche move and topout on black fins. The topout is about 20 ft. up with a sandy landing.

Also has a sit/traverse called Xenolithic var. or Quickstone, is prolly V5. Sit start on the left side of the small cave at an undercling, traverse right about 6 ft. on slopes and small crimps to the first triangle sloper. Finish up Psyche.
,
Spotters are desirable on this one
]

Location: Alisters Cave > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This problem is a super classic, and perhaps the best problem of its grade in Joshua Tree. Essentially Caveman's big, secluded brother. Climb the sustained roof on jams, edges and heel hooks with a dynamic finish on sloper slapping. Some trickery allows you to completely recover before launching into the final sequence. The plastic-trained climber who loves gymnastic moves on relatively large holds will adore this one.
,
At the far right side of Alister's Cave is a chalked jug and overhead handjam slot. Sit start and work through the roof ending at obvious jugs in a break just above the dismal finishing slopers.
,
A single pad will suffice, but have a spotter who can drag it as you climb. If you're solo and at your limit two pads would be nice.
]

Location: Coyote Corner > Echo Cove Bouldering > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

This is a fun highball problem or mini solo that will leave a smile on your face. Climbs the obvious left-facing corner and then the heavily featured face above.

Although quite tall the business is over around the 20 foot mark and the top section is nothing but fun climbing on jugs.

,

The obvious corner system on the north side of the clump.

,

Several pads and a spot if you think you might fall.

]

Location: Texas Boulder > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start from the right side of the concave scoop, stem out left to make a reach to knobs at the lip and then fire for jugs just below the top.

Consider this the bouldering equivalent of the game Twister.
,
Located on the west face of the boulder, just around from Border Patrol and not visible on the approach.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Manx Boulders - Northwest Face > Manx Boulders > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Make a high-step smear into the concave scoop and reach up to a sloper, stand it up and mantle into lower angle terrain directly above.
,
On the far right side of the Manx boulders, just left of the Right Arete starting in a concave scoop and finishing straight up. Descend by chimneying down between the two Manx boulders.
,
Pad.
]

Location: False Hueco Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start on the low rail and work up on small crimps and knobs to a short slab.

,

Just left of False Hueco.

,

Pad

]

Location: The Blockhead > JBMF Boulders > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
standing start. move up and left
,
in between Yabo Roof and False Up 20 boulder. walk between the two medium sized boulders
,
pad and a spotter. a bad fall and you could pinball
]

Location: Chunky Boulder > Chunky Boulder and Trance Stone > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This climbs the overhanging, juggy arete. Fun, overhanging climbing. Too bad it isnÂ’t longer. ItÂ’s about 5.8. Descend the low angle slab. Flat landing.
,
Whatever.
]

Location: Wave Boulder > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Slither up the balancy arete which curves up and left to join the Descent Route (V-easy/5.5) near the top. Deceptively impressive and always worth your time.
,
The curving Northeast arete of the boulder.
,
pad
]

Location: Scorpion Roof > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start and traverse right on good huecos. At the right side of the cave move out to the lip and make a hard move to gain good holds in a slanting crack.

Follow the crack past a break until possible to move left into a scoop. The crack is not hard, but you feel exposed as you make your way higher. From the scoop either traverse left and downclimb onto the boulder, or continue directly up.
,
Starts on the left side of the cave.
,
Pads and spotters
]

Location: Pothole Rock > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climbs a grainy arete/dihedral with a flaring crack and slopes. The Mantel is the hard part, but that is to be expected here. Not a fun top out for shorties.
,
Pad and spotter.
]

Location: Wedge Boulder > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This goes up the low-angle, Southwest arete. The arete is beautiful and a bit high.
,
Nice, soft, sandy, landing.
]

Location: Miledi Boulder > Miledi Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This superb problem is found in the center of the north face and features excellent grey stone throughout it's length. Lieback a right-facing flake to about two-thirds height, make some committing moves to get stood up on the top of the flake and then ease your way to the top - the ground is a long ways down at this point!

The base is flat but sloping so you might want to terrace your pads to level it out. A sit start can be done which adds a few more moves and bumps the grade up to V5.
,
Several pads and a spotter is nice
]

Location: Pinched Loaf Boulder > Western Belt > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Power up the shallow, overhanging left-facing corner past a prominent, rounded black knob and a slanting lip. Short but demanding.
,
West face of the boulder.
,
Pad, spotter
]

Location: Manx Boulders - Northwest Face > Manx Boulders > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This short arete problem is one of the easiest on this circuit and a decent warm up. A couple of sidepull moves gain lower angle terrain.
,
On the far right side of the Manx boulders, facing Cyclops. To descend, either downclimb this problem, or the easy chimney between the two boulders.
,
Pad.
]

Location: Triangle Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
A classic slab problem with slick footholds and, thankfully, decent handholds. Smear up greasy holds at the start to gain a jug near the right arete and then work back left to a high finish on some hollow flakes just right of the boulder's apex. An easy downclimb is found on the backside.

Rated V0 in several bouldering guides but it seems a bit harder - do this problem and do Intersection Boulder, Left, and then decide which is more difficult.
,

Keep your friends, and yourself honest. The down climb is alright, flare chimney off the back Â between the huge boulder to climbers left , and the Dab Rig. Ohh yeah and donâ€™t mantle the thing too aggressively and eat shit over the other side..Â

Location: Sandy Wash Corridor > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
At the right end of the All Washed Up wall, boulder up to a prominent horizontal 10' off the ground and traverse left about 6' to a good pair of slopey holds on the rail. Decent feet set you up for a pretty easy dyno to the sloping rail above. Can chew your hand a little if you keep missing it but much easier than the dyno of Saturday Night Live, for instance. Could probably be done statically. Definitely a fun little problem. A perplexing direct start exists but without more or less lunging off the ground looks hard (supposedly V4)

Smooth landing, not too high.

The brief crux consists of a few very sloping pulls and is probably best done when temperatures are cooler to ensure success.

If you loved Caveman (which you should have), you'll love adding another 10 move compression problem to the beginning of it! Seriously, it's full value and awesome. Start under the "belly" of the Caveman holds and squeeze and heel hook your way to the start holds of Caveman (V7). Go do it!

Location: Pixie Boulder > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Starts out on the far left on good jugs, then traverses inwards as per Skimbles. Move into a knee bar, then through a few slopey pinches made better by a better knee bar. Bump right hand to a slopey pocket, then match, then a fully spread horizontal move to a right crimp, followed by bringing the left foot into a heel hook for a fairly low accuracy left hand bump to a razorblade crimp near the lip. Continue traversing R either through two decent crimps, or, jump to the slopey bread loaf out right and top out. Super fun route!!!

Tis a variation of Monkey Gone to Heaven and Skimbles, that stays predominantly inside the bowl of the boulder.

StokedÂ to finally send this route out in Indian Cove. Its an extended variation of Skimbles on Pixie Boulder that adds a few harder moves including a rough match, and a low accuracy move to a tiny left razorblade crimp. Two years ago, i fell on the second to last move. Grateful to finally send and surpass my previous self, despite the trials and tribulations of the last years. Yeiiii!!!! Lets go!!

,

Starts in same place as Monkey Gone to Heaven and ends in same place, though the path stays predominantly inside the bowl and only uses the lip once on a tough crimp.

There is one more line on this, maybe v10, that doesnt use the lip at all. Will come back and finish.Â 

]

This is an excellent problem for the grade with fun movement and just enough height to make it somewhat exhilarating.

Downclimb either Cleavage or a gritty 5.6 fistcrack on the back (south) side.

Location: The Cube (aka Funktion Boulder) > Scatterbrain Area > HVCG North > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
A tall, classy old-school boulder problem. Start via either a dynamic move to a crimp or perhaps from cheater stones if present. A few big, fun lockoff moves lead past a rail and on to better holds further and further above a rather dicey landing. The topout isn't too perplexing, but it does involve a little slab at the very top and you're pretty far off the deck.
,
As per the Function boulder, this problem is on its south (or southeast?) face (not the one with a rivet ladder). I think there must be an easy downclimb on the back part because I don't recall any shenanigans.

A few pads would be nice but falling from the top is probably not a good idea anyway.

Location: Lakeside Rock Formation > Barker Dam Boulders > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

This sexy crack is a great intro to invert offwidth bouldering. This problem is a lot easier than it looks. To begin, sit start in the far back of the crack feet facing towards the exit. Start holds are best with right hand on the right-side pinch rail and left hand on a tricky/hidden fin-like dish found on the opposite wall. There is a great foot hold found lower on the pinch rail that can be used to pull yourself up into the crack to begin the brawl. Stay cognizant of the several cheater holds. Top out finish can be easily downclimbed to climbers left.

,

The Sunchild Tribute can be found atop the Lakeside Rock formation. As you enter the open area of the Barker Dam from the main trail, the boulder/crack can be seen atop the right side of the Lakeside Rock formation directly in-between the top-outs for the roped routes "X-Rated Tits" and "Parental Guidance Suggested".Â 

You can approach the boulder several ways. You could potentially climb and top-out several of the sketchy rope routes at the wall OR there are also easy 4th class scrambling up both the left and right sides of the formation. The climbers left side of the formation requires boulder scrambling initially, followed by low-angle slab that takes you across the top of the summit boulders where, traversing right, you will end up on the top of the Sunchild Tribute. The climbers right side of the formation requires steeper scrambling up a water shoot that passes a medium-sized tree, then, just past the tree, scramble up a short chimney exiting left at the top to end up at the bottom of the Sunchild Tribute.

GPS coordinates: 34.030960, -116.143488

,
Boulder pads
]

Location: Yoda Head Boulder > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

[

Stem up the "corner" of the yoda head boulder to reach the lip. Pull the lip.Â 

Be careful with fall potential, there is a drop off that'll add a good 20+ feet to your fall if you miss the pads and or have a bad spot.Â 

This route is an absolute classic, it was full of skrittle on the FA but was definitely climbable and will just get better with traffic.

  • Here's a video story for the FA if you're interested in checking it out -

https://youtu.be/08RzevRd8FM

,

Go to the Room to Shroom area. From Room to Shroom the "Yoda Head" Boulder is on the climbers right side of the canyon. Not far from Room to Shroom walk deeper into the boulder field. Once you're walking in you'll see it on your left side (right side if facing Room to Shroom)Â 

The boulder should only be about 5-10 minutes away and is very noticeable.

,

Pads/spotters. Big drop off in the fall zone

Location: Entrance Boulder > Entrance Boulder & Vicinity > Real Hidden Valley Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
A classic run and jump problem. The V6 rating is not mine, but has been tossed about. As far as jump problems go, this one is pretty hard and is probably J2+. It is harder than the run and jump on Streetcar Named Desire, and miles harder than the Jump Chump.

Start well back from the South, and then sprint headlong at the boulder, trying to launch up and right to the obvious patina rail that is high above. Finish up and right on easy ground.

Here is a video link to "The Driver" trying this problem in the '80's. fishproducts.com/movies/driâ€¦
,
On the front (South) face of the Entrance Boulder. Scramble off the back.
,
Boulder problem, with cat like skills your only protection. A pad at the base may affect your approach run, and for sure removes style points.

This brilliant problem features some of the better rock in the Park and is well worth a visit.

Start with your left hand in a vertical seam and your right hand underclinging a small overlap then work up to good incut jugs on a smooth face. Get your feet high and power up over a small roof to some nice incut holds. Once above the roof good holds lead to the topout. A sit start can also be done and checks in at around V6.

Location: Tidal Wave Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This line takes the northeast arete of the boulder. Two good holds at about head height, one on each side of the arete, will get you started. From there, horrible left hands on dimples and texture (calling them "holds" is kinda laughable), some heel trickery, and positive but well spaced right hands will take you to the summit. Probably the most do-able of the problems at this grade in JT, reachy but not too morpho. Due to the minute, sloping nature of half the holds, you'll want cold temps.
,
This is the namesake problem on the Tidal Wave boulder. The boulder is directly adjacent to Dino's Egg and the Iron Door Cave, in the Outback. From the HVCG, walk out past the Nixon cracks and the boulders are on the left, sort of across from Roof Romp which is about 100yds away.
,
A couple of pads is nice. The landing is flat, but there is a large ledge/boulder/ridge kind of thing that is possible to hit (likely with your head if you did) that you'll probably want to pad. Recommend 2-3 pads and a spotter or two.
]

Left edge of the East face (facing the road).

pad

pad

Location: Dino's Egg > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Grab the rounded edge of the hueco, make some steep moves as you pull into the hole and get stood up. Now the fun bit as you work slightly left and out of the hueco with handholds that get more sloping the higher you get as the bulging wall pushes your lower body out. Ignore the boulder below, get the balance right and top out. Note: It's possible to step off the problem midway onto the boulder below but at a certain point you're committed, although you can also traverse off right to finish on The Clutch.

This is a good problem, but one best appreciated by those not bouldering at or near their limit on this.

,

Located in the middle of the south face, between Platypus on the left and The Clutch on the right, at a distinctive hueco. You'll also notice a large boulder set back from the base - position a spotter on this to push you off left should you pitch from up high.

,
pad, spotters

pad

Location: Dripper Boulder > Human Sacrifice Cove > The Volcano Area > Virgin Islands Area > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start at a right-slanting flake and then stem and contort your way up and left until able to reach into the bottom of a widening flake. The crux is controlling the swing as you commit to the flake but shorter climbers may disagree with that. Once established in the flake make a few airy moves and mantle over on jugs. A short bit of easy but exposed face leads to the top. Quality.

Downclimb by heading to the left and then down a slab with some knobs which will get you onto the shelf above Driblet, where a quick hand traverse and final easy corner will get you to the ground (see photo).
,
Center of the West Face.
,
pads, spotter
]

Location: Gram Parsons Memorial Boulder > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
You'll find this large flake of rock on the northwest side of Cap Rock, visible from the road. Named for the memorial at the base to Gram Parsons, a former musician in The Byrds and The Flying Burrito Brothers, as well as some solo work.

Traverse the slightly overhung, jagged flake for roughly 25' and then drop off - or do some laps. A good warm-up for the harder problems nearby or enjoyable on it's own.
,
pad

pads

It's hard for the grade (even for JTree).

Just right of Locker's Chimney in Forgotten Boulders.

Pad

Super unique and cool looking boulder, but the consensus among the three climbers I was with is that it's V2 / V2+ (the guidebook rates it a V4**). Definitely worth checking out though, not only for the boulder, but for the absolutely beautiful view.

Joshua Tree / The Underground / The Heart of the Universe

North side of the boulder.

NE corner of Texas Boulder

pad

Actually found on the boulder immediately behind Strawberry Contraceptives. In other words, if you are looking at SC, turn around and there it is. After topping out you can climb down a slabby dihedral or just hop off.

Location: Tidal Wave Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
SDS at the southwest arete, move right and past the overhanging northeast arete of Tidal Wave at twin sidepulls and then traverse the smooth patina face using thin edges, sidepulls and creative body positioning to reach the Bedrock Arete which is taken to the top.

As an alternative it can be done from a stand start at the Tidal Wave arete using a flat edge on the left side of the arete and sidepulls on the right (this is the version described in the bouldering guide) which makes it slightly shorter and perhaps a little easier.
,
North face of the boulder.
,
Several pads to cover the base
]

Location: School Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start on two crimps over the lip of an arete, pull up and right to a tiny crimp work your way up on crimps and slopers till you hit a huge sloping rail then top out. Very balancy and extremely sandbagged. Very fun problem.
,
On the side towards the large rock formation, the starting arete forms the mouth of a rock hall way.
,
One or two pads
]

Location: Pothole Rock > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climbs the rounding buttress/arete. Look for the slight dishes for feet and trust them. There are pretty much no hands until you hit the obvious dish halfway up.
,
Pad
]

Location: Mirage Boulder > Western Belt > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Starts from a high pinch hold and moves left along a horizontal crack until possible to continue up using a slot and gain the top.

* A really good problem but there's no way this thing is V4.
,
Pad, spotter
]

Location: Mel's Diner Boulder > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start on the left shelf and traverse right on jugs. Many variations possible.
]

Location: Hoi Polloi Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Grab some head high jugs, pull up and over the small roof and gain a stance below the smooth chocolate slab. Make a few easy slab moves to gain a good edge and then enjoy the moves to the top.

  • This is a fairly tall problem but the positive nature of the moves make it easier to commit.
,
Located on the left side of the north face, 10' left of Prince Fari and below a smooth black slab.
,
Pad, attentive spotter(s)
]

Location: Chocolate Boulder 3 > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start with hands either side of the arete. Pull on and make a couple of big moves up the arete, before leaning a long way over to the left and the good holds on Torpedo.

Finish as for Torpedo.
,
north west arete
,
Pads
]

Location: Meadows Boulder > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start sitting at a curving rail and head directly into the crux which is possible via two ways - either crimp a narrow slot before firing up for a horizontal, or go big and launch directly for it, and then top out with an easy mantel.
,
Left side of the west face.
,
Pad
]

Location: Ayatollah Boulder > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located on the west face of the boulder, just left of center and identifiable as face leading into a shallow right-facing corner; there is a large rock and a bush near the base of the problem as well.

The crux moves on this are low as you work off a sharp crimp onto a small edge for your foot, but a bit higher, at the start of the corner, is the mental crux as you must commit to a high foothold to reach the temptingly close jugs in the corner. Easy moves lead up the corner to the top and there's an easy descent to the right.

Fun moves on good rock but you really don't want to fall off this once you're past the crux.

Named for it's slight resemblance to The Ayatollah (5.11b/c) at nearby Cap Rock.
,
pads, spotters
]

Location: Orange Julius Boulder > HVCG East > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start in overhanging huecoish terrain to gain small crimps at the bottom of the dike. Pull a straightforward but powerful, reachy sequence on tweaky edges with little to no feet. Once your feet are established on the dike, the difficulty eases.

Favors tall climbers. At 5'9" I was campusing between edges through the crux.
,
The completely obvious orange dike.
,
Pad/spotter.
]

Location: Boulder Crack Rock > Planet X Area > Planet X Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

SDS and make surprisingly difficult moves up the overhanging thin to hand crack to a lip where the angle kicks back and the hard climbing is over.Â 

  • The problem can also be done from a standing start at about V1.
,
Right side of the northeast face.
,
pad
]

Location: Facet Boulder > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This climbs the double aretes on the south end of the boulder, to a mantle.

Pad.
]

Location: Texas Boulder > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Yabo (sit) start on low crimps with high heel, make a long lock off to the starting horizontal crack of Border Patrol (V1).

Far right corner of the Texas Boulder.
,
Pads
]

Location: Chocolate Roof > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start on the left side below the roof. Traverse rightwards, until possible to reach up to the lip. Reach above the roof for a good, but small crimp, and from there jump to the good holds on the arete above.

Finish up the short arete.

Climbs the roof just right of center

Pads and spotter

Location: JBMF Boulder > JBMF Boulders > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start with one hand on the arÃªte and another on a small edge and then bump up to a good sloper, get into balance and then rail out the arÃªte all the way to the top of the boulder.

,

Left of the JBMFP is this striking right-slanting arÃªte problem.

,
pad
]

Location: Papa Boulder > Hemingway Boulders > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start from the arete and a jug and then make balancy moves up to gain a slanting flake near the top where a mantle caps off this fun problem.Â 

Can be done from a sit start at about V0.

The downclimb is the easy crack on the backside.

* Listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide as #78, Unknown.

,
The northwest arete of the boulder.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Chuckawalla Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This is the left most line on the Chuckawalla Boulder and is approximately 10' left of Chuckawalla (V1).

This easier problem (5.8) climbs a prominent right-curving arete with jugs from a standing start (the sit start is about V1 or so).

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree bouldering guide (it does show this problem in the photo for the boulder) but it's an obvious line with good movement on solid patina holds making this another problem worthy of inclusion to a circuit of the area.
,
pad
]

Location: Family Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This problem starts a few feet over from the left arete on nasty crimps and polished feet, gaining the right slanting seam and following it until you can mantle over the top. Getting established on the face from the ground is a battle in itself. Taller people will find this easier than short folks.
,
Start 3' right of the left arete, at an obvious crimp, gaining the seam after a move.
,
Pad
]

Location: Voices Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start at the sharp arete of Mr. H, then traverse right onto the right boulder and finish up Voices Arete. Â 
]

Location: Trashcan Boulders > Trashcan Rock Area > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This problem is located on the front of Trashcan Rock (facing the road).

It's the crack furthest to the left, a powerful move up to easy climbing. The descent is a little bit scary but worth doing the climb.
,
Pad, spotters
]

Location: Seven Grain Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This fun problem climbs the slanting and overhung northwest arete of the boulder and is much better than appearances might first suggest.

Sit start at an incut rail, get your feet set and then surf the arete left - sometimes using the lip of the arete and other times using holds further back - to a cool sequence below the lip and then polish it off with a classic mantle/rockover move onto the top.

Fun and athletic in nature, this is another great moderate problem of the area.
,
pad
]

Location: Texas Boulder > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start with a head-high side pull for your right hand. Big feet. Roll over and reach high left for an opposing sidepull. Throw right and exit with a standard Josh mantel.
,
NE corner of Texas Boulder
,
pad
]

Location: Manx Boulders - Northwest Face > Manx Boulders > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Gain the good sharp crimps, and via a high step and sidepull reach up to the sloping finishing holds.

Good crimpy climbing for the grade.
,
Left of center
,
Pads
]

Location: Dino's Egg > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This problem is found above the sit down flake (V2) on the second tier of the Dino's Egg boulder.

Start with a good left sloper and an in-cut right hand using the positive rail on the underbelly (see picture). Move to a sloper and head towards the jug above the lip, finishing with a not-a-gimme mantel (see picture). Squamish style and a bit thuggy.
,
the dino's egg
,
one crash pad
]

Location: Scorpion Roof > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start as for Scorpion Traverse.

Move out to the lip of the roof. From the lip make a hard move to gain a poor sidepull for your left hand. Bear down and reach up to the slopers at the horizontal break. It takes power to keep hold of the slopers as you match and traverse right into the crack.

Reach the crack and take a breather before finishing as for Scorpion Traverse.
,
Climbs the roof direct.
,
Pads and spotters
]

Location: Black Lichen Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This challenging and balancy problem climbs the rounded arete/corner right of Joker (V1) via creative body positioning as you work the rounded, sloping holds until near the top where you can rock over and finish onto the slab.

Due to the sloping nature of the holds this problem is best done when the temps are cool and your hands are in shape for pulling on the rough rock - caveat emptor!

Still cleaning up a little so don't be surprised if a little loose grit is present.
,
The rounded arete just right of Joker (V1).
,
Pad, spotter(s)
]

Location: Semi-Precious Boulder > Semi-Precious Bouldering > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This is the cool plated crack on the south east face. It's about 5.8. This can also be used for the descent.
,
Pad.
]

Location: The Hatrack > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start on right side pull and use the solid jug to the right of Porkpie. Â Transition out of this and move into the start of Porkpie. Â Finish as you would for Porkpie.
,
Just to the right of Porkpie.
,
Pad.
]

Location: Trashcan Boulders > Trashcan Rock Area > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
On the main face, left of The Trough (5.0) and Karpkwitz (5.6) is a thin white dike cutting up a face. Pull onto really nice edges of the dike. Care is required topping out due to the height, but jugs abound.

Left of The Trough and Karpkwitz on the main West Wall of Trashcan rock. Across the way from the Forgotten Boulders proper.

A pad or not.
]

Location: Hensel Boulder > Scatterbrain Area > HVCG North > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located just right of Slabmaster is this standardized friction test. A decent problem if in the area but the nearby Intersection Boulder, Left is a better problem if that sort of thing interests you.
,
Center of the East face (facing the road).
,
pad
]

Location: False Hueco Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
An eliminate, but still quite fun. Start Anti-Heuco, move directly up to edges, then use only the right side of upper hueco before a big move to the lip
,
same start as False Hueco, finish just right
,
Pad, spotter
]

Location: Little Big Horn Boulder > Little Bighorn Area > Asteroid Belt Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start underneath the boulder in the same place as for Sitting Bull. Instead of going left as for Sitting Bull, go right to a high sidepull, then up.Â 
,
To the left of Little Bighorn. Start on the obvious cracked patina holds near the ground at the low roof.Â Â 
]

Location: JBMF Boulder > JBMF Boulders > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Â Starting off a shelf of rock, climb edges up a smooth slab to a finishing jug.

,

West face of the boulder and just right of the Hensel Face.

,
pad
]

Location: Trance Stone > Chunky Boulder and Trance Stone > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Same start as Trance (V7), but fire up and right to the rail and move right and up into the saddle. Flat landing.
,
pad
]

Location: Under Lizzy Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start as for problem B, move up and into a corner
,
Pads
]

Location: Campsite Grotto > HVCG South > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Sit start at far end of the cave. Jam, crimp, squeeze, and invert your way up and out, then follow a low angle crack/slab to the top.

A few eliminate variations exist. If you don't use the right boulder face for your feet after existing the cave, it bumps it up to a V4.

,

Up the hill from Bittersweet , in a little cave

]

Location: Gunsmoke Wall > Gunsmoke Area > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Begin on low jugs somewhere left of High Noon on Gunsmoke Traverse. Make a dynamic move to the jug at the beginning of High Noon, then climb left on the rail and up the face above via edges; crux move is a throw to/pull from a sloper and is more difficult than High Noon. Not sure of "exact" location of start; can be done from the beginning of Gunsmoke, as can High Noon. Thinner top-out as well, if I remember correctly.
,
Same as for Gunsmoke and High Noon.
,
Crash pad; spotter to keep you away from yucca and/or rock in landing zone.
]

Location: Split Boulder > King Dome Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

SDS at a flake and then make balancy moves to get established on it before moving right onto the steep slab, working up rounded bumps to the top.Â 

Cooler temps help on this problem as the handholds are quite sloping in nature.

Somewhat of an eliminate at the crux as you come very close to, but don't use, holds on Blurb.

,
Center of the left boulder between Canasta and Blurb.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Black Pea Boulder > Triangle Two Boulders > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb the slab past the namesake â€œBlack Peaâ€ feature.

Adjacent to the Triangle Two Boulder. Easy downclimb to the left.
,
Pad and spotter.
]

Location: Friction Slab > Gunsmoke Area > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb directly up the middle of the slab after a hard start.
,
On the boulder opposite The Chube.
,
Pads
]

Location: Embryo Boulder > Embryo Area > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This problem is on the side facing away from the road. Move up a right diagonal rail to steming up a concave face.
,
Head, Hands and feet.
]

Location: Sandy Wash Corridor > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
A fun highball with a scary crux near the top.

Start easily up the thin crack, and gain a good ledge below the widening crack.

Layback the crack for a scary sequence until possible to move into the wide top part of the crack.
,
This route lies on the South Face to the East of the wash.

Pads and spotters

Location: Halfling Boulder > The Hang > Planet X Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This run-and-jump problem kicks off a small edge and launches up for the distant but incut lip of the boulder above.

Right side of the north face.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Chuckawalla Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Yabo sit start as you would for Little Chucky, but instead of moving out right, move left and straight up the boulder. Strenuous gaston move out to the left makes this more difficult if you're shorter.

Sit start as for Little Chucky.
,
1 Pad

Location: Native Arete Boulder > Indian Wave Boulders > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Extending an excellent problem to make an equally good problem and more sustained problem.

Sit start facing left and climb the arete directly to join Native Arete.

SDS to Native Arete.
,
Pads
]

Location: Baby Face Boulder > Western Belt > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start at the middle of the face, head up and right to the upper right arete of the boulder.

Right most climb

pad

Location: Discount Dyno Boulder > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start matched on a juggy horizontal crack and dyno to the rounded top. The usual grainy mantle to finish.

Located on the east face of the boulder.

,

Pad

Location: Mel's Diner Boulder > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sidepulls up to rails and buckets.
,
Start on the left face of the boulder onÂ an arching crack.
,
Pads
]

Location: Simpleton Rock > King Dome Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Crank patina edges past a finger pod, then make a reach to gain a jug at the start of the crack system. Once established in the crack rail out right to finish and descend the backside.

Fun moves on quality rock are found on this problem which is somewhat technical for the grade.

Located on the south face of the boulder and identified as thin face leading into a right-slanting crack system.
,
pad
]

Location: Flight Attendant Rock > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Thin but positive edges on dark patina lead up the overhanging prow to a crux dyno/reach to a shallow dish and a finishing mantle.Â 

Great moves on stellar rock make this a favorite of the area.

  • If your fingers want more crimping, do the sit-start (V7).
,
On the northeast prow of a small boulder just just east of the sharp Gibbs Arete.
,
A pad or two, a spotter is nice for the top section
]

Location: Chunky Boulder > Chunky Boulder and Trance Stone > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This climbs the center of the slab to the left of Â“ChunkersÂ”. A high step over a low incut section leads to a few unexciting moves up edges and smears. ItÂ’s about 5.9. Flat landing.

Whatever.

Location: Cap Rock > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This problem is encountered after about 125 yards, when approaching from the parking lot. This is a slick thin crack with a cruxy face at the top. Don't fall! Not much chalk on this one.

Skill.
]

Location: Camp Boulder > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
On the north side of the boulder, sit start at the right end of a horizontal crack, move left and finish with a blunt arete above a small roof.
,
Pad.
]

Location: Mullet Bloc > The Separate Boulders > The Wastelands > Queen Mountain Base > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
SDS at jugs and work out right and then back left onto the smooth brown slab using nice but sharp incut edges and the occasional pocket, the largest being called " Tinkerbell's Anus". Interesting moves on great rock.
,
Right side of the west face.
,
Pads, spotter
]

Location: No Name Boulder > Gunsmoke Area > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start on lower rail, and paste the feet. Go for a right crimp then fire up to the left sidepull on the original. Finish as for Unnamed.
,
Lower start to Unnamed.
,
Pads
]

Location: Big Dike Boulders > Echo Rock Boulders > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This starts at a crack and traverses diagonaly left along a dike. Either walk to the right rear of the rock and hop across to the "Big Dike" boulder and down it's back side or down-climb the crack.

Pads and spotters.

Location: Scoop Boulder > Jimmy Cliff Area > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

Work up the dished-out face midway to the crux where it suddenly gets steep and a delicate and committing smearing sequence demands your attention. Once past the angle kicks back and it's easy friction to the top.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.

Left side of the east face near an arete.

Downclimb by heading to the left and then down a slab with some knobs which will get you onto the shelf above Driblet, where a quick hand traverse and final easy corner will get you to the ground (see photo).

Right of center on the West Face.

pads, spotter

Location: Chocolate Roof > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start on the left side of the roof. Traverse underneath the overhang, and round the arete on the far right. Continue along rightwards to good handholds, then launch for the lip of the boulder and mantle it out.
,
climbs the roof on the far right side, where there is no roof!
,
Pads
]

Location: Semi-Precious Boulder > Semi-Precious Bouldering > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This climbs the scooped face, several feet left of Hot and Juicy (5.8).

Pad
]

Located just right of Voices Arete (V-easy) on the west face of the Voices Boulder.

This is a technical lieback problem with slippery hand and footholds that require a bit of thought. Tough for the grade and best done when shady or cool.

pad

Location: Hensel Boulder > Scatterbrain Area > HVCG North > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start with hands on good holds, then move into the scoop and high gastons from which the crux moves allow the rounded mantle finish to be reached.

North end

Location: Newton's Law Boulder > Planet X Area > Planet X Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

North side of the block

pad

Location: Chuckawalla Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This problem is a link-up of Flintlock Dyno (V0) and Chuckawalla (V1) on the Chuckawalla Boulder.

Start on Flintlock Dyno with both hands matched on the large, flat edge and then reach up and left to a couple of edges (one good edge, the other not as good). Once established on these holds work way left using creative body positioning to the big edge midway on Chuckawalla and finish with the last moves of that problem.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree bouldering guide but is an obvious line with good movement on solid patina edges making this another problem worthy of inclusion to a circuit of the area.
,
pad
]
