Location: Roof Boulder > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start low in the cave and move up the juggy rails until they die out, then bust a big move out left and move straight up to top out. Many would say it's soft for the grade.
,
Middle of the roof
,
A pad or two and maybe a spotter. The landing is somewhat sloped.
]

Location: Black Lichen Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climbs the right side of the Black Lichen Boulder; the problem Ace lies about 10' to the left.

The crux comes early as you press out some thin edges and you bring your feet up onto a high shelf. Once on the slab work your way up the high-angle slab via sloping edges and delicate footwork to a commiting high-step just below the top. Downclimb via a juggy crack to the left which splits the boulder into two.
,
pad
]

Location: The Peanut Boulder > Volcano Boulder Area > The Volcano Area > Virgin Islands Area > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start as low as possible and climb the highball face trending left over the boulder. Scary!
,
Right of the human sacrifice cove area. Pretty easy to find.
,
Lots of pads and a couple spotters! One spotter should be on the boulder keeping the pad under you.
]

Location: Caveman Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start on a bad pinch and sloper, go straight up to prow, and top out.
,
On Hit And Miss Boulder facing east which is just south of Caveman Boulder.
,
crashpad
]

Location: The Asteroid Boulder > Asteroid Boulder Area > Asteroid Belt Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Refer to picture topo under Pea Brain V4.

There is also a sit-start from good obvious holds under Pea Brain, traversing right into Mighty Dog. Not sure of the grade.Â 
,
on the asteroid boulder
]

Location: Psycho Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Harder starting moves lead up and slightly to the right to easier balancy moves with a good topout. Really fun and varied movement, do a few laps.

,

Shares the start to the middle face route "Unknown", but takes the more natural path up and to the right.

,
A pad or two. Nice to have one for the downclimb too, located around the left corner.
]

Location: Anvil Boulder > Varnished Wall Boulders > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

SDS at the base with opposing sidepulls and work incut edges up and left moving onto the arete proper. Work back right via a high-step, then mantle up onto a shelf below the top - a quick reach and easy mantle caps off the problem.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
The northeast arete of the boulder.
,
Pad
]

Location: Stoney Point Boulder > Towers of Uncertainty > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start in a shallow hueco and move up on decent crimps (and a good left hand mini-bucket) to a slopey topout. Make sure to pad the boulder behind you.

,

Stoney Point boulder

33.9661862, -116.0852780

]

Location: Romp Roof > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start as for Flake Direct and climb up to the start of the flake. Break left, and reverse the moves on Roof Romp, continuing past the traditional start until you reach the chossy corner.
,
Pads
]

Location: Strawberry Contraceptives Boulder > The Hang > Planet X Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
A great climb. A sit down start is possible (v6-ish) which starts on the good left edge of the crack and requires a hard layback with a good right foot. Pull yourself up to better right hand holds and use a left undercling. Make a powerful move up, dance your feet out and find increasingly better laybacks up to the juggy top out.

Very fun!
,
Follows the crack to the left of Strawberry Contraceptives. Easy downclimb/hop off the backside.
,
crash pads and spotter
]

Location: So High Boulder > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
A cool circus move from the left facing jug sets you up on the face. Move left towards the "buttons" with a couple of reachy moves. Continue up and left to the summit. Hard move are getting established on the face. Scary moves are moving left.
,
On the SW face of the So High boulder. Starts in the undercut scoop/dihedral with the left facing jug overhead.
,
Pad if you think you need it
]

Location: The Pig Sty > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start at a sloper on a blunt arete and climb the slab with balancey moves and small handholds.

The Miramontes guidebook has it at V2.Â 
,
The left side of the large, obvious slab seen when first entering the Pig Sty. It is to the left of the Unnamed V0 slab problem that uses the large flake/undercling.Â 
]

Location: The Watchtower > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start matched on small ridges, hit a left crimp/pinch above, then pull and thrust out right to a good sidepull. Easier climbing from there to top.

,

Joshua Tree / The Underground / The Watchtower

34.0499556,-116.1031417

,
Pad or two and be cognizant of the yucca.
]

Location: Pro Tip boulder > HVCG North > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
A decent little boulder problem. Stand start with your hands on the large sloping ledge, then use a classic dish w/ thumb catch and some other bad holds to make it to the lip. Sit start is awkward But fun and goes at the same grade.
(Starting right foot is crumbly but should get better with traffic)
,
On the left/north side of the of the pro tip boulder.
,
One pad tops.
]

Location: So High Boulder > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This is the traverse under So High. Starts on low sidepulls and traverses right. It used to connect with So High, but some holds broke.
,
really tough fingers
]

Location: Pixie Boulder > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
SDS at the obvious rail and head up and left to finish with an incut rounded mantle.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Northwest corner of the boulder.
,
pad
]

Location: Indian Wave Boulder > Indian Wave Boulders > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start at the obvious high crimps.

Move up left and make a long reach to a good sloper for the left. From here traverse powerfully rightwards, either on poor slopers, or powerful crimps.

Make a hard move to gain good holds just left of Old Wave, and then finish easily straight up to the left of Old Wave.
,
Center of the NW face
,
Pads and spotter (to move the pad)
]

Location: Tips Be Gone Wall > Western Belt > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Crouch start as for Tips Be Gone. After the move up left continue traversing left on good hand holds. When these run out launch up left to small but positive holds in the holes up and left.

Continue left on improving holds to finish.
,
Mid Right to left traverse of the wall
,
Pads
]

Location: Mel's Diner Boulder > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start on the left side of the main face and move directly up on jugs, getting balancey with smaller holds at the top.
]

Location: Manx Boulders - Northwest Face > Manx Boulders > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb the easy crack.

Not much of a climb, but it can act as a good descent.
,
Around the arete from Out of Touch.
,
pads
]

Location: House of Mirrors Face > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

House of Mirrors climbs the center of the black streaked face on quality rock. Â Steep slab moves to a large side pull and good edges higher up the face. Â 

,

Behind Collieherb Boulder. Visible from the Cap Rock parking area.

,
Pads, flat landing
]

Location: Meadows Boulder > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

A fun compression variation to Raspberry. This looked like the more obvious line to me when I first saw the boulder and it may have already been climbed. It isn't listed in the 2012 guidebook but the holds underneath the roof were ticked when I did it.

Start as for Raspberry but instead of matching the jug, move left to a crimp rail, staying underneath the roof. Bump the right hand and set up for a big left-hand move out to a flat sloper. From there, finish up the arete on good holds.

Video: youtube.com/watch?v=prJ3zyuâ€¦

]

Location: Meadows Boulder > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Mr. Meadows has done it again! The best boulder in the park just got even better. Sit/lay down start with no pad on two slots. Bust out left to slopers and make a big crux move right to another sloper. Finish up the warm up corner trending left.Â 

Beta video: youtu.be/I-VyEDlq6Wg

,

On the far left side of the meadows boulderÂ 

]

Location: Stem Gem Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Jump off the small boulder, which gets lower the closer you are to the Stem Gem boulder. Catch the sloping hueco. A challenging mantle follows.
,
Just to the left of Stem Gem, obvious jumping boulder is obvious.
,
Probably can get away with 2 pads.
]

Location: Arete Boulders > Echo Cove Bouldering > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This is the first problem encountered coming from the parking lot. It climbs the short overhanging arete on the right.
Photo by Blitzo.
,
Pad.
]

Location: Satellite Boulder > Planet X Area > Planet X Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start bottom edge of the hanging boulder behind Satellite Boulder. Campus up to good edges then crimps and slopers lead you to the top

,

Found on the suspended boulder behind and to climbers left of Satellite.

]

Location: Campsite Grotto > HVCG South > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Listed as 5.8 in a guidebook. Climb the left arete and slab of the giant 20 foot flake sticking out of the ground. Downclimb or jump off onto the nearby slab. Getting off the pinnacle is a bit tricky.

,

About 50 feet to the east of Bittersweet v9.

,
Don't fall!
]

Location: Caveman Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start on Caveman and launch right into thin and sharp crimps, then make a small but slightly desperate move to good holds. A fall has the potential for injury without a good spotter.

,

Start of Caveman.

,
Couple pads, A spotter or a hanging pad for back-grinding rock
]

Location: Black Rock Boulder > Black Rock Canyon Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Scramble up a few feet and start matched on ledge at the bottom of the overhang. Work up and out left using the arete to pull onto face of boulder. Top out on jugs. Enjoy the exposure!

A few other boulders could go on this rock.
,
Multiple pads. Rocky landing.
]

Location: Alisters Cave > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Its been a long time so it is a bit fuzzy but.....

Stand start by any means to get onto the face above the chest high roof. Trend up and right via nice face climbing. Gain a nice muffin on the lip/arete. Mantle onto the slab and top out.

,
In between the notch on the approach and the cave itself.
,
Pads
]

Location: Facet Boulder > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start leaning off the right side of the arete, find your feet and power up to better holds above.Â 
,
This boulder is found on the North side of the Headstone formation.Â 
,
2 pads
]

Location: Trashcan Boulders > Trashcan Rock Area > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Thin face just right of Butterfly crack. Joins that route around the 20 foot mark
,
TR or pads
]

Location: Dover Cliffs Boulder > Trashcan Rock Area > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

A tricky layback problem following discontinuous seams up a steep slab.

,

SW face of the boulder.

,
Flat/soft landing
]

Location: Mind The Gap > Volcano Boulder Area > The Volcano Area > Virgin Islands Area > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

The technical crux is the first few moves of slab. Once the arete is gained it is a pleasure cruise to glory. The arete is great but the feet are small enough to keep your attention.

This would get all the stars if the slab to the left wasn't there. It doesn't interfere with the climbing but it does make it possible to avoid the crux by starting the line off the slab.

,

The line faces away from the trail so you will just need to walk into the cluster to find it. It is pretty straight-forward.....its the giant arcing arete that you will want to climb when you see it.

,

4 pads did us right....but we didn't fall :) 2 will flatten out the stepped landing to the left of the star and 2 will offer some protection for the rest.

]

Location: Hemingway Corridor > Hemingway Boulders > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start with hands on the top rail all the way to the right. A small right foothold on the arete will get you started. Traverse right to left until you hit the large apex, rock onto the slab, and top out. Excellent quality rock,Â great movement, and an easy landing make this a classic.

,

If youâ€™re looking at the Oak Tree Boulder slab, it is the A-frame looking peak directly behind it. Start on the far far right and move left and rock onto the slab to finishÂ 

,
Pad
]

Location: Psycho Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Traverse the wall R->L, starting on some small slopey holds and moving to the first crack (crux) before working your way past the other cracks. Keep chugging and gain some height toward the end before topping out above the small roof. Better than L->R due to the more logical topout, but this whole wall has great rock and is just fun to mess around on.

,

Looking away from the main face of the V50 boulder, this wall will be on the right side of the canyon less than 100 yards away.

,
Pads for the tricky bits, pretty low overall. Spotty yucca is poised and ready to strike.
]

Location: Spicy T Boulder > Western Wilderness Boulders > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start on the boulder at the base of the crack. Follow the crack up and left until the positive holds run out. Throw around the corner to a nice edge then cut feet and swing left to exit on the ramp.
,
Couple pads and a spotter.
]

Location: Hemingway Corridor > Hemingway Boulders > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Sit start with right hand on a good edge, left on rail. Get a heel on and fire up to the lip, proceed to traverse to the furthest peak on the right and mantle.Â 

,

If youâ€™re facing Islands in the Stream, Twin Peaks is located directly behind you, and below The Laying of Hands problem.Â 

]

Location: Group Site Boulder 5 > Group Campsites Road > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start on the low rail jug, and go directly up.

,
crash pad
]

Location: Stoney Point Boulder > Towers of Uncertainty > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Climb a ramp into a knobby dihedral. You can escape out to the left early but the true line follows the corner all the way to the top. Overall, quite easy but a fall onto the ramp wouldn't be too enjoyable.

,

Stoney Point boulder

33.9661862, -116.0852780

]

Location: Zinger Boulder > Semi-Precious Bouldering > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Per the Miramontes guidebook: "Jump and mantel the obvious dish." The guidebook has it at V2/3.
,
This is on the side of the Zinger boulder that is facing the road. You can see the dish from the road.Â 
]

Location: Sandy Wash Corridor > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start as for Lunge for it, but go straight up over small bulge and then top out on slopers and a crack higher up. Falling off top lands you in a bush frequented by bees.
,
Right side of Sandy Wash corridor
,
Pad, Bee keeper's gear
]

Location: Hoi Polloi Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located on the northwest face of the Hoi Polloi Boulder, about 8' right of Prince Hoi (V2) where the patina starts to become less uniform and more broken.

Start to the right of a lighter patch of rock shaped like the African continent, and work up incut patina edges and plates trending slightly left until they end and then finish up a grainy but solid slab (the slab finish is shared with Prince Hoi). The easy downclimb is found on the east (backside) of the boulder.

This is a study in contrasts with it's steep, positive holds at the start and lower-angled balancy slab as you get higher above the ground - classic Josh bouldering!
,
pad
]

Location: Animal Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start with a sidepull and pinch. Work up to another pinch, then pull onto the slab.
,
Pads
]

Location: Big Moe Wall > Echo Cove Bouldering > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Reach up high for an incut shelf. then either move up and left along a slopey sidepull, or use a sidepull crimp to the right (crux) to reach a good horizontal pinch. Continue up a bit more on easy terrain until you're about 20 feet up. Move carefully right along a ramp with decent (but not perfect) jugs and rails until you make it to safe ground.

The crux is the first few moves, so none of the danger coincides with the difficult climbing. Still, carry your chalk bag with you

,

Starts just left of a tree and right of an 11c sport line (ground up or shutup)

,
Optional pad for the start, after that it doesn't matter
]

Location: Parking Lot Boulder > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Jump start to a jug and a great mantle.
,
Right side of the parking lot boulder, can't miss it.
,
Pad
]

Location: Johnny Dawes Boulder > Gunsmoke Area > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start by standing up onto the rail and finish straight up the boulder but with a twist...huck a 180 and finish sitting facing gunsmoke! Remember, NO HANDS ALLOWED!

]

Location: Psycho Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Reach up and grab the starting holds. Steep moves with no feet gets you up and established on the slab. Way off the deck climbing gets you to the top
,
Kinda flat but a large rock behind you is a hazard.
]

Location: Bullet Proof Boulder > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Slippery feet and an under cling start the problem. Move left to match on thin crimps then throw for the butter dish up and slightly right then mantle the rail to the left.
,
The route on the left.
,
Flat with a boulder to watch out for.
]

Location: Psycho Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Sit start. Match on a large slanting ledge. The under cut feet make for a tough start so a high left heel hook comes in handy. Pull up and throw for the next good hold. Then traverse left staying low until you can exit via the crack/seam. Or keep traversing past the crack another five feet and mantle onto the slab.

,
Good landing.
]

Location: Lox Boulder > The Separate Boulders > The Wastelands > Queen Mountain Base > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This is a traverse right from the 'Tosspint' start hold. Traverse right to small crimpy flakes topping out on the shelf on the right of the arete
,
This problem is located on the Mullet Bloc 2 or also called the Lox Boulder about 20 feet up the base of the mountain from the Mullet Block.
,
Crash pads. Good landing area but s couple rocks on the floor of the landing zone. Just cover with a pad.
]

Location: Psycho Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

This rock is to the left of the main psycho boulder. Stay outside of the rocks and walk to the left. Hidden in the tree's. Sit start on the far right side and start traversing the lip until you go around the corner and up to the good top out hold. Heel hooking is mandatory! For the direct start match on the jug in the middle of the rock fire to the lip and mantle over.v1

,
Good landing.
]

Location: Sidekick Boulder > Big Brother Boulders > Hall of Horrors Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This is the left-leaning, juggy crack on the East Face. It's about 5.9.
,
Pad.
]

Location: Dike Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start at the pointed knob, then traverse the dike to a jug.
,
Pads
]

Location: Cave Rock > Towers of Uncertainty > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Obvious and fun cave/roof feature on Cave Rock.
,
In the middle of the base of Cave Rock. Problem #15 on Shaun's mini topo.
,
Pad
]

Location: Small World Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
SDS as far right as you can at a hoizontal crack and follow the crack up and left until possible to make a reach for the juggy incut lip above where an easy mantle caps it off.
,
North side of the boulder.
,
Pad
]

Location: Chocolate Boulder 2 > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This climbs the flared corner between Boulder 2 and the Chocolate Chip. Sit start at the back of the flared corner, rail out left via a crack and then make crux moves getting turned into a lieback position. Once established a few more moves conclude this problem.
,
Pad, spotter
]

Location: Split Boulder > King Dome Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Climb the slab via sloping holds to reach a shallow crack at the top and finishes with a mantle with a juniper in your face - watch your head! Traverse left and tunnel through a hole in the juniper to descend the backside.

  • Can be done from a sit start at V0 or so.
,
Located on the right side of the Split Boulder near the center of the block.
,
pad
]

Location: Orange Julius Boulder > HVCG East > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

At HVCG to the right of Orange Julius (Bachar route) and Lemon (V3). Start on the obvious jug (hueco/hole in rock) and traverse right on the sloper rail for 15 ft or so. Rail turns into a crimp rail as you traverse. Dishes for feet. "Top out" up the ramp.

For style points, climb in crocs & no pad. Prob not first to do this traverse, but documenting it because it's good fun!

,

Located in HVCG site 43, to the right of Orange Julius Boulder -- directly behind the firepit.

,
spotter and crocs
]

Location: Bluff Boulder > Echo Cove Bouldering > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Jump start to a good hold and then work your way up right to top out.

,

This climb is found to the left of Monkeyflower

,
Two pads
]

Location: Maverick Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start at the left side of the face with good patina edges for your hands and your feet below you on a flat ledge of rock. The crux is getting your feet over the undercut bottom of the boulder and onto the face, after which it's a fun series of plates and jugs up the tall face to an easy topout.

Fairly high with a flat landing and solid holds the whole way making this a fun problem to stretch out on and enjoy the view.
,
Located on the south face of the boulder and just left of Renegade which climbs a juggy right-slanting seam.
,
pad
]

Location: Family Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb the slab just to the right of How's Your Mama on very thin sharp edges. Maybe more straightforward than the afformentioned problem, but very thin and sharp. Yowza!
,
pad
]

Location: Tips Be Gone Wall > Western Belt > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Crouch start with hands on the lowest of the obvious holds.

Pull on then immediately make a hard pull up left to a good break. From the break bust a move up to a small crimp up right. From here work your way over onto the slab and the finish.
,
Middle of the wall
,
Pads
]

Location: Illicit Sweetie Boulder > The Hang > Planet X Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Jump to the sloping lip, mantle.
,
On the left (South) side of the boulder.
,
pad
]

Location: Entrance Boulder > Entrance Boulder & Vicinity > Real Hidden Valley Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start off a small shelf and lieback the obvious hole as you highstep into it. Once established work up and right on large incuts with smears for your feet to an easy topout.
,
On the Southeast corner of the boulder at an obvious hole in the rock.
,
Pad
]

Location: Seven Grain Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This tricky slab problem climbs the smooth slab left of Dances With Weasels. Tough friction with one good crimp for the right hand as you work your way up glassy smears to some larger holds just below the top.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Center of the south face and just right of the apex of the boulder.
,
pad
]

Location: Dino's Egg > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start with a high left hand, pull onto the rock and then up and right to match on a large patina plate. Leaving the plate, which is the last positive hold, work slopers over the rounded top and get your foot up onto the starting holds before rocking over. Short and fun and a lot less scary than it's neighbor just right.

,

Located on the left side of the south face just left of a large hueco which is Dino's Egg.

,
pad
]

Location: Chocolate Boulder 2 > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Starts 10' left of Bodacious and climbs sweet edges up and right to join the top of Bodacious. Features good incut holds the whole way with some attention to footwork and balance needed as well as just enough height to get your attention without being dangerous or scary.
,
pad
]

Location: Campfire Circle Boulder > HVCG South > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start up a short slab, make contorted moves over a small roof to slopers and finish up an arete. Tough for the grade. An easy downclimb exists on the west side of the boulder just right of the Crystal Arete.
,
Just right of the Weenie Arete.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Simpleton Rock > King Dome Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start around and right from The Simpleton from a low start and work up the slightly overhanging juggy arete to the crux just below the top as you transition around the arete and join the top of The Simpleton. Mostly positive holds the whole way but a good spot is necessary to keep you off the boulder at the base if you pitch. Descend the backside as per The Simpleton.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Just right of The Simpleton on the juggy arete.
,
pads, spotter to keep you off a rock at the base
]

Location: JBMF Boulder > JBMF Boulders > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
After a jump start, or a pad assisted step up, onto two jugs you dyno onto the lip and finish off this short but entertaining route.
,
To the right of JBMFP on the lower section of the boulder.
,
Pad, Spotter.
]

Location: Scratch-N-Sniff Boulder > Miledi Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb thin edges on good rock directly up the north face of the boulder, just right of Scratch Arete (V0).
,
pad
]

Location: Turnbuckle Rock > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start right of Turnbuckle and lieback up the curving arete to a rounded mantle finish - probably about 5.9 in difficulty. An easy downclimb is found on the backside (East face) of the boulder.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
15' right of Turnbuckle.
,
pad
]

Location: Shipwreck Boulder > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Jump start to the good jug, get a quick toe and hand jam and work up to a good top out. If you eat it, take some time while lying on your back to admire the petroglyphs.
,
North side of the boulder, around and right of Fist Full of Walnuts.
,
Pad, spotter
]

Location: Intersection Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This boulder is located on the east side of Intersection Rock (hence the name) and sits out away from the formation with another smaller rock next to it (the smaller rock has a worthwhile 5.9 mantle on the east side). There are three problems on this face - the left one is V1, the middle one is V2 and the right one is V3. They are all kinda sketchy, so make sure you have some spotters and some pads.
,
spotters, pads
]

Location: Xenolithic Boulder > Loveland Bouldering > Pinto Basin (aka Eastern Territorries) > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This problem traverses the exotic South face. This traverse boasts some of the most unusual holds in all of Jtree - Multi faceted huecos in bullet hard black rock, pockets, mailslots, basketball sized enclaves that make huge open-handed jugs, and finishing with the black morphic gneiss of Psyche.

Start at huecos on the far left side of the overhanging south face. Traverse right 20 ft. on all sorts of rad jugs (avoiding a low boulder), V1 jugs all the way till the end when you link up to Psyche for the finish moves.
,
A spot is nice for the finish, which is quite steep for its height.
]

Location: Melon Boulder > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Powerful opposition moves at the start gain a small hole to a classic finish up a balancy thin face passing a small grey knob. Quality.

Rated V2 in previous bouldering guides but it seems a bit harder than that.
,
Right side of the east face between Melonizer and Enter the Melon.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Maverick Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
The easiest way up and down this boulder.

Climb up the good patina in the middle of the wall.

  • Listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide as #671, Unnamed
,
Middle of the west face
,
Pads
]

Location: Hobbit Hole Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start just right of center and climb up the slab using small flakes and slopers.

If you like slabs, you'll lap this up.
,
Located on the small slab to the right of the off width
,
Pads
]

Location: Blas Beemer Boulder > Blas Beemer Area > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start under the overhanging base of the crack, and lieback your way up into the stand start.
,
pad
]

Location: Nixon Cracks > HVCG North > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
A nice tips crack leads to a wide slot, then sweet jams to the top of a vertical face.
,
The rightmost boulder length crack when looking at Nixon cracks.
,
pads
]

Location: Little Big Horn Boulder > Little Bighorn Area > Asteroid Belt Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb up small edges to gain the right facing flake. From here finish direct.
,
Center of the wall, just to the left of Burning Sensation.
,
Pads
]

Location: Hensel Boulder > Scatterbrain Area > HVCG North > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
That's not V1!

You might be thinking that as you look at it, but no, it really is. The combination of just enough holds and a series of enjoyable moves make this a problem that's deserving of more attention.

Start under the bulge and monzo-navigate your way upwards to a hidden hold, a standard mantle finish being the topout.
,

Backside (west face) of the boulder; faces away from the road.

,

Pad

]

Location: Powell Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start with underclings under a small roof. Throw up and left to a small ledge, then dyno for the shelf.

,

On the right hand face. Starting underclings are well-chalked and obvious.

,
pad
]

Location: Split Boulder > King Dome Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Bumpy slab leads to a left-facing flake that is underclung and then liebacked to a comitting and somewhat gritty mantle at the top.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Center of the right side, between Solitaire and Fish.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Mel's Diner Boulder > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
A fun problem involving big moves on big holds. Right of the wide crack, start on shelf jugs and toss to the next horizontal. Finish on jugs.
]

Location: Mel's Diner Boulder > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start on the right side of the right face and follow jug rails to the top. Also a good downclimb.
]

Location: Entrance Boulder > Entrance Boulder & Vicinity > Real Hidden Valley Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start from a large incut jug and lieback up the arete using a slanting seam/crack on the right. Balancy with good body positioning required.

  • A SDS can be done at about V3.
,
On the Northeast corner of the boulder.
,
Pad, spotter to keep you off the rock to the right.
]

Location: Tidal Wave Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This problem is located around the corner from Bedrock Arete on the Tidal Wave Boulder and faces west. One or two powerful moves on crimps and slopers with difficult feet are the gist of it. Although short, it is clean and certainly worth trying when in the area. Good landing.
,
Pad
]

Location: Echo Rock Proper > Echo Rock Boulders > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
A fun (and long) traverse in the classic Echo slab style, found at the base of the main West Face. I did it starting at Double Dip and finishing at Stichter Quits, but either way is good. From Double Dip, the traverse starts easy and gets progressively harder, with the crux coming around the base of the route "Gone in 60 Seconds". The climbing involves thin edging and friction, and the rock is totally clean (prolly from the billions of people piddling around at the base). Its possible to climb higher or lower, but my feet never went higher that 5ft from the ground.
,
Pads optional!
]

Location: Papa Boulder > Hemingway Boulders > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Starts in the center of the face at some high edges. Use of creative body positioning will allow a reach to a good left hand sidepull and then a high edge for the right before the topout. Quality.

  • Listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide as #79, Unknown.
,
Center of the North Face.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Powers Boulder > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Low start at an incut rail to the left of the arete. Power over (don't dab) and join Little Tool up the arete to finish it up.
,
Pad
]

Location: Interceptor Boulder > Asteroid Boulder Area > Asteroid Belt Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located just left of center on the west face of the Interceptor Boulder.

Lieback up a flake making some balancy moves with slick feet and then reach up for a juggy horizontal crack before topping out on more jugs - watch out for the cactus at the top! An easy downclimb is found on the east face (backside).
,
pad
]

Location: Belly Roll Boulder > Semi-Precious Bouldering > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
On the South end of the boulder, climb the right diagonal crack to a mantel onto the slab above.
,
Pad.
]

Location: Chocolate Boulder 1 > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climbs the slabby north face of the boulder via crisp, thin edges on excellent dark brown rock. The start is the crux and is undercut with sloping smears for your feet; above it gets much easier.

Rated 5.9 in the bouldering guide but it's a bit harder than the nearby Mini-Slab.
,
pad
]

Location: Mel's Diner Boulder > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
The tallest problem on this formation. On the furthest right face, mantle onto a rounded shelf and then mantle again onto a large shelf. Escape left here or pull more jugs for another 7 feet to top out the formation.
]

Location: OK Corridor > Planet X Area > Planet X Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Walking into the corridor this problem will be found on your right just as you enter. Slabby and somewhat committing, this problem has the hardest moves down low but a fall from the top is best avoided.

Â Descend off the slabby east face or by down climbing just left of OK Face.

,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Sacred Land Boulder > [Redacted] > Sacred Land > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Jug haul to a nice campus finish. On the boulder "Painted Savage 1", south facing. Start low on jugs and traverse left to a shelf and a more juggy finish.
,
Southeast side of the Sacred Land boulders, south face. Opposite from "Painted Savage 2" boulder.
,
Pads
]

Location: Strawberry Contraceptives Boulder > The Hang > Planet X Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb Loose edges/plates up and left, on the outside of the boulder from strawberry.
,
back side of strawberry
,
pad
]

Location: Showstopper Rock > Real Hidden Valley Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Work the NW arete just off the path. Sharp left hand crimp up to a vertical rail.
,
From the trailhead after entering the valley, follow the trail right...up and over a small ridge as if going to Sail Away. Once you walk over the small ridge, boulder is immediately on your right.
,
pad
]

Location: Jimmy Cliff Boulder > Jimmy Cliff Area > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climbs straight up the center of the nice grey slab with positive edges that appear when you need them the most.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Center of the north face.
,
Pad
]

Location: Dino's Egg > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start in the middle of the face at the obvious positive crimp and climb directly up the face.
,
Middle of the west face
,
Pads
]

Location: Wave Boulder > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This climbs up/down the featured left side of the South Face.
,
You may want a pad.
]

Location: Strawberry Contraceptives Boulder > The Hang > Planet X Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Match start on rail, hike up your feet, and go for the lip.

,

Southwest side of Strawberry Contraceptives boulder, between two smaller boulders.

,
Single Pad
]

Location: Caveman Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Awesome traverse with sweet moves that will test your rubber! If youâ€™re looking at Caveman, go right and around the corner until you see some large, shallow dishes. The traverse starts on the right at a â€œpillarâ€ between dishes. Traverse left using creativity, delicate feet, and some black magic. Finish by climbing up onto the pedistal and topping out.
,
If youâ€™re looking at Caveman, go right and around the corner until you see some large, shallow dishes.
,
Pad
]

Location: Sports Challenge Rock > Real Hidden Valley Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sick of sketchy highballs? Tired of polished rock? If you said yes to any of those questions, than this is the climb for you! Start matched on a slopey cresent and slap through shallow dishes before toping out at the apex. Lowball. The adjacent boulder is off.
,
This boulder lies just behind the west face of the Sport Challenge Rock
,
A pad if you're not afraid of dabbing
]

Location: Star Boulder > Western Belt > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Discountinous hand crack on the far right side of the overhanging face. You lose the crack for the topout, but feet are great and there's a decent loaf to grab on for the topout. Exhiliarating.

I recommend checking it from the top to see where the good hold is and where to place your pad in case of a fall

,

Far right end of the overhanging face. Obvious crack

,
Pad
]

Location: The Pig Sty > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start the problem with either balancy moves on delicate hands and feet or fire dynamically for the obvious crimp rail just out of reach above. Move into the flake and carry on up and over the top on the nice holds.Â 
,
Center problem on the south face of the boulder with the crimpy sit start boulder problem on the west side, Unnamed V5. This problem is in the sun most of the day. There is a cave on the right that seats four.
,
Single boulder pad minimum.
]

Location: Nixon Cracks > HVCG North > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Walk up onto a big flake on a steep slab. Reach far left for a seam with a fin, then lay it away and prepare for a desperate sloper finish.
,
Just left of Left Nixon Crack.
,
pads
]

Location: The Hatrack > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Directly behind the Handicapped Parking at Cap Rock is a long, low boulder (The Hatrack) with boulder problems on all sides of it.

Right of Sombrero (V1) and left of the obvious parking sign, on the west face of The Hatrack, is where this friction slab is found. Remember - it's all in the feet. One star out of five.
,
pad
]

Location: Unnamed Boulder > The Hang > Planet X Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

From a sit start, climb the diagonal crack. Â 

To downclimb from the top, step onto the adjacent slab boulder.Â  Â 

,

Look for the obvious diagonal crack. Â If you are looking at the Nicole Overhang from the Dragon Scales (Illicit Sweetie) boulder, the crack will be toward the right.Â Â 

]

Location: Land of the Lost Boulder > Echo Cove Bouldering > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start squatting at the base of the hanging arete. Climb the overhanging arete on big holds. 11ft tall with an uneven landing.Â 

,

The arete on the far right side of the boulder.Â 

,
pads and spotter
]

Location: Intersection Rock > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Starts from small edges at the lip of the intial scoop where tricky footwork up the steep slab gains larger but sloping holds up and left. Getting your feet established over the lip is the crux after which it's fairly easy to the top. Head left over the top of the crack and then back to descend.
,
Just right of Knuckle Cracker up a scooped face.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Dike Boulder > Lechlinski Cracks Area > Virgin Islands Area > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start on jug in the beginning of the dike. Move up and right to a finger stack pocket and two horribly low angle pockets. Continue into "Cleavage".
,
pads
]

Location: Tour Boulder Two > Tour Boulders > Lechlinski Cracks Area > Virgin Islands Area > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Tricky balance moves at the start lead to edges and slopers concluding with a high and somewhat insecure finish. Good pad placement and spotting is helpful on this problem.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Center of the east face between Rob's Prob and Cinders.
,
pads, spotter
]

Location: Chocolate Slab Boulder > Human Sacrifice Cove > The Volcano Area > Virgin Islands Area > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climbs the center of the clean slab via delicate friction and precise footwork. Descent is off the backside.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
West face of the boulder.
,
pad
]

Location: Garden Angel Boulder > Hall of Horrors Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start at a large, round flake. Use good feet to pull straight up and over a bulging, slopey top.Â 

The Miramontes guidebook has it as V1.Â 
,
On the only side of the boulder that appears easily climbable. This problem is to the left of "Under the Garden Angel Right." It starts at the large flake/plate.Â 
]

Location: Shocked Quartz > HVCG North > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start on some knobs lower on the face, then climb past the quartz patch.
,
Pad.
]

Location: Facet Boulder > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This climbs a patina face to a mantel finish, to the right of Riff Raff, on the East Face.
,
Pad.
]

Location: Manx Boulders - Southeast Face > Manx Boulders > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
A mantle problem, and a good warm up for the harder ones on the North face.

Move up easily to gain the good hold on the lip. Now reach up and secure the jam before mantling onto the hold.

Will that jam stick?
,
Right side of the South face
,
Pads
]

Location: Chuckawalla Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
A variation on little chucky with a finish that rivals the start.

Begin as for little chucky. After reaching the jug rail, head back left using thin edges to join the finish of Chuckwalla.
,
Pad and plenty of stoke
]

Location: Turnbuckle Rock > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb the short but sweet slab (5.6) via some balancy smears on good rock. This would be a good problem to learn balance and movement and is also useful as a descent.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
South face of the boulder and just right of a bush.
,
pad
]

Location: Land of the Lost Boulder > Echo Cove Bouldering > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
SDS at large scoop feature, pop for good right hand pinch/side-pull follow good holds to the top.
,
Right of chorizo taco stand
,
Pad
]

Location: Thunder Egg Boulder > Boyscout Trailhead Bouldering > Wonderland of Rocks North Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start on low opposing crimps and figure out how to pull onto the rock. Move up and slightly left.

]

Location: Roof Boulder > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Yabo start at a jug on the left, then follow the line of slopes rightward, as far as possible before moving to the lip.
,
Ryan Campground
,
Pads, spotter
]

Location: Meadows Boulder > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This problem contrasts nicely with the others on this boulder - delicate and technical.

Start left of center. Get established and move to the middle of the slabby wall and continue more or less direct to the top.
,
Located on the center of the North face
,
Pads
]

Location: Illicit Sweetie Boulder > The Hang > Planet X Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start below the undercut slab and move up on marginal holds to get established on the low-angled slab which steepens at the top.

  • In the Miramontes bouldering guide as Mulligan Slab.
,
North side of the boulder and just left of a catclaw.
,
pad
]

Location: Anvil Boulder > Varnished Wall Boulders > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Stem off a boulder on the right to reach a good sidepull, toe onto the rock and then reach for a good flat edge. Match the edge, get your feet up then go for the incut lip. Fun moves and much easier than it looks.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Just right of center and a prominent black streak on the north face.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Manx Boulders - Southeast Face > Manx Boulders > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Run up the rust streak and latch the high jug of Thingamajig.
,
Pads
]

Location: Chocolate Chip > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
The low-angled southwest arete goes at 5.7 and has great rock and fun moves. Too bad it's not two or three times taller.
,
pad
]

Location: The Arrowhead > Sacred Land > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Mantel a black knob, then mantel the top. This faces Northwest.
,
Pad.
]

Location: The Hatrack > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Directly behind the Handicapped Parking at Cap Rock is a long, low boulder (The Hatrack) with boulder problems on all sides of it.

This is the first problem right of the parking sign on the west face of The Hatrack and climbs a slippery slab on slopers with one positive but sharp edge. Make sure you're shod in your slippers when you send this short sandbag that's best done in the shade. One star out of five.
,
pad
]

Location: Split Boulder > King Dome Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb the rounded arete right of Blurb with the hardest moves coming at the start. This problem is also useful as a downclimb for this side of the boulder.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Right arete of the left boulder, just right of Blurb.
,
pad
]

Location: Forgotten Boulders > Trashcan Rock Area > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This is the prominent chimney with a chockstone at the top, on the Westside of the formation. ItÂ’s about 5.6. This chimney goes all the way through the rock.
,
From the dumpster, walk about 20 yards around the left side.
,
The landing gets worse, the deeper you go into the chimney. Don't fall.
]

Location: Mel's Diner Boulder > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Yabo (sit) start from the crack on the bottom right. Traverse over to the left with good feet, hands will require some technique and balance. Once you have traversed over to the left of the main bolder continue up to the right and top out at the horn.

Named Mel's drive-thru because it is located on the back end of the Mel's Diner Boulder.

Are you taking some gym climbers out to Jtree for their fist time outdoors? Well stop on by Mel's diner!!! While your real rock virgins test their fresh hands on that rough Jtree grit, Â swing over to Mel's drive through where we have had reviews like, "I hate whoever found this climb" and "that was interesting" even "should be a V2". Add to the list of comments after you ignore your fledgling gravity fighters for a few minutes and take a ride on Mel's Â Drive-Thru!!!

,

If you are looking at the main bunch of Mel's Diner Boulder, this is to the right still connected to main grouping of rocks.

,
Two pads, could use one and move. Spotting will only be necessary at the top out.
]

Location: Planet X Boulder > Planet X Area > Planet X Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Climb straight up the face using an assortment of crimps, pinches and even underclings to a high finish on good holds. The crack to the right is for sure off route! Probably done long ago but who knows?

,
Between Planet X and Wormhole.
,
Several pads and spotters are nice.
]

Location: Ninja Boulder > Gunsmoke Area > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start with hands matched on a good rail and a heel hook on a better rail lower and too the left. make your way up the small slopey crimps to a bomber ledge and top out.
,
A pad or two and definitely a spotter
]

Location: Boulder 1 > Lonely Stones 2 > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Sit start at a nice horizontal pinch thing. Move up on good holds. The Miramotes guide calls this V1, but I can't see it.

,

Centerline on the southern face of the boulder. In line with the peak

,
pad
]

Location: Hoi Polloi Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Standing start below two small crimps. Make hard moves to gain a good left hand hold and then make harder moves to end up standing on the small crimps.

Reach up to better holds, and then pull through these to the top.
,
Right side of the NW Face
,
Pads
]

Location: Mullet Bloc > The Separate Boulders > The Wastelands > Queen Mountain Base > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Lieback your way up the offset seam that transitions from slightly overhanging to a slab. The crux is a tricky section midway with thin edges as you work your feet to the lip.
,
Center of the west face.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: The Purple Helmet > Western Belt > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start up vertical slashes to gain a prominent black flake which is liebacked on the way to the top. To descend downclimb as far as possible and jump off.
,
The obvious line on the northwest face.
,
Pad
]

Location: Family Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Pull onto the footrail, go to the good high sidepull/undercling flake directly overhead and then mantle it out. Easier for tall people who can reach the good high hold from the footrail. Shorter people will have an extra move that will be the crux for them.
,
On the far right side of the boulder is a large foot rail, a couple of crimpy sidepulls and an obvious good sidepull/undercling up high.
,
Pad.
]

Location: Group Camp 1 Boulders > Group Campsites Road > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This route climbs the right Arete as you look at the north face.
,
Back of Group Camp 1. Walk off.
,
Crash Pad.
]

Location: Grit Rock > HVCG North > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Double pinches straight up to slopers (Dyno is cheating). Excellent rock quality!

,
Rightmost problem on the boulder.
,
Pad
]

Location: Little Big Horn Boulder > Little Bighorn Area > Asteroid Belt Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Pop or lunge? That is the question.

Bit of a one move wonder, but worth the entertainment.

Step on and grab the crimps. Now make your way to the good hold in the middle of the slab. From here finish straight up.
,
Right of center on the North West face.
,
Pads
]

Location: Forgotten Boulders > Trashcan Rock Area > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This challenging problem climbs a rounded buttress on sloping holds and palm-intensive slaps and is tricky for the grade, especially if the weather is warm.

Starting from a good right-hand sidepull and left-hand sloper work your feet up to some good edges as you slap your way up rounded holds to some better holds near the top. This problem is best done on cooler days, as it's considerably harder when the temps are high.
,
Located just northwest of the crack and arete problems near a secluded picnic table.
,
pad
]

Location: Pygmy Boulder > King Dome Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

SDS at a large plated edge and make a long reach/throw to an incut plate (shorter climbers may need to bump off an intermediate gaston) and then to the lip where a mantle caps it off.

  • Better than it looks with an easy descent just to the left.
,
North side of the boulder.
,
Pad
]

Location: Igneous Boulder > Echo Cove Bouldering > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start on low left horn and right jug, pull gaston moves up and left into the concave, pop for juggy crimp and pull for plates above
,
left of igneous ambiance
,
pads, beware of rock beneath
]

Location: Garden Angel Boulder > Hall of Horrors Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start to the right of the large flake/plate. Use the diagonal crack to climb up to the lip. Mantel over.Â 

The Miramontes guidebook has it at 5.9.
,
On the only side of the boulder that appears easily climbable. This problem is to the right of "Under the Garden Angel Left." It uses the obvious diagonal crack.Â 
]

Location: Meadows Boulder > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start as per Sloper Safari (V4) at a low shelf and work up and right on horizontal slashes (staying low where Sloper Safari heads up) to match on a curved thin hold (crux) and then make a long reach/throw for the upper horizontal which is traversed right a ways before manteling over the top.
,
Center of the west face where the rock starts to become undercut.
,
Pad, a spotter might be nice at the crux
]

Location: Double Orifice Boulder > HVCG East > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start in the lower of two large huecos, climb out through the second hueco and over the bulge to top out. Fun movement, very atypical for Jtree.
,
pad
]

Location: False Hueco Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start as for False Hueco. Pull up to the rail on the left and make a powerful cross on the rail. Continue to move left with a bump to a good crimp sidepull and thumb catch.

Pull onto the slab and finish as for Torquemeister.
,
Left side of the boulder
,
Pads
]

Location: Slash Boulder > Western Belt > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

SDS with hands matched on a large flake and low feet, reach up and right to match on the first horizontal seam and then wander up the horizontal slashes to finish with tall but easy slab.

  • Â The problem can also be done from a standing start at about V0.

* This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.

,
Left side of the South Face and around and left from Seam Splitter.
,
Pad
]

Location: Matatte' Boulder > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Difficult to start... Either jump or stack some pads to reach crimps. Then move up and slightly right on grainy crimps and slopers. Walk up up slab to finish.
,
This is the right side of the tall face behind the Moffatt boulder. Start is to the right of the cave.
,
Pads
]

Location: Pork Chop > Lonely Stones > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
SDS at a dark-colored flake and follow it as it curves up and left to a mantle finish.
,
Northwest face of the boulder and visible on the approach.
,
Pad
]

Location: Dino's Egg > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Hang off some big huecos at the start with the right side of your body against the rock on the right - it can't be helped - and then work up and left into them and then up to finish, or better yet, by heading slightly right and stemming up a concave patina groove to finish. Make sure to have some spotters ready as falling at the wrong spot on this wouldn't be good.

This is a decent problem with some fun moves and good rock but the contrived start detracts slightly from the overall experience.Â 

,

Located on the right side of the south face, just right of an obvious hueco which is Dino's Egg and left of a block which is the other half of the Dino's Egg Boulder.

,
pad, spotters
]

Location: Little Big Horn Boulder > Little Bighorn Area > Asteroid Belt Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Steep jug hauling.

Climb the very steep left arete of the North West face.
,
Left arete of the NW face.
,
Pads
]

Location: Manx Boulders - Northwest Face > Manx Boulders > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This short but engaging problem is on the far left side of the Manx Boulders just left of Grunge (V0), an obvious lieback flake, and about 30' left of Off Camber (V4).

A short section of liebacking gives way to a rounded top where one must make the most of slopers and dishes before pulling over the top. One star out of five.
,
pad
]

Location: The Asteroid Boulder > Asteroid Boulder Area > Asteroid Belt Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Around and right from Nebula, on the other side of the flake that contains that is problem is this right-facing flake to a huge black jug. The problem Pioneer is found about 10' right at a left-facing flake.

Grab the flake high, get your feet onto a horizontal and then work the flake higher as you smear your feet over a slight bulge to reach the obvious jugs before mantling over the top - fun!

This problem is unnamed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but given the name Ceres here due to it's resemblence to the symbol (a sickle with a crossbar at the bottom) for that dwarf planet/asteroid - click here for more information about Ceres.
,
pad
]

Location: Saturday Night Live Boulder > Real Hidden Valley Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Night Crawler backwards. Slightly harder as crux at corner involves stepping down, rather than stepping up. Recommend doing Night Crawler to start or run start between the two bushes

,

Start at the end of Night Crawler (by the large bush)

,
Optional pad
]

Location: The Womb > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Traverse along the lip of a slightly overhanging boulder near The Womb. Â Start on the side closest to The Womb and traverse for a foot or two before rounding the corner and moving to the much longer side with a single black streak running down its center. Â Reach the end of the longer side and round a second corner before topping out on the slab side. Â The lip is an obvious rail about 8-10 feet off the ground. Â There is a small boulder on the ground near the first corner to be aware of. Â 

[Not listed in the guidebook, but seems like an obvious line.]

A note on the name: The climb is adjacent to a popular boulder and v-easy called "The Womb," which arguably has a faint resemblance to an actual womb. Â I like it when climbs in an area or on a specific cliff/boulder all stick to a single theme in how they are named, and when I name new climbs, I always try to keep with the existing theme. Â The thinking here was that this problem sits just below The Womb, in a figurative sense like how a cervix sits below a womb in a woman's body. Â So the idea was that these two boulders are like two parts of anatomy that go together.

,
About 20-30 yards west of The Womb (toward Park Blvd) among a small patch of boulders.Â  The edge will be obvious.Â Â 
,
Crash pad.
]

Location: Tilt-o-Meter Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Traverse the Tilt-o-Meter boulder by climbing through the three Tilt-o-Meter problems. Â You can start from the right and move left, or you can start from the left and move right--they go at about the same grade. Â 

If starting on the right: Start at the top of Tilt-o-Meter Right standing on the shelf and move down onto the rail (basically doing the climb in reverse), then hit the jugs on Tilt-o-Meter Center by making use of the large flake, then climb Tilt-o-Meter Left and top out. Â 

If starting on the left: Start at the left-most hold higher up on Tilt-o-Meter Left, move down and right to the large flake, move up to the jugs on Tilt-o-Meter Center, then move to the rail of Tilt-o-Meter Right and finish on the shelf with an easy mantel.
,
Northeast corner of the boulder
]

Location: Grit Rock > HVCG North > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Stem up the concave.Â 
,

ConcaveÂ face to the left of Feel the Grit.

]

Location: Meadows Boulder > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb the right side of the arete using thin plates and edges, up to a large flat shelf at about 15 feet. Execute an exposed and attention grabbing mantel, hand-foot match, and reach for the lip. So, so good.
,
This problem is located on the tall Meadow 3 boulder, located about 20 meters behind the main Meadows boulder. On the left arete, while facing the steepest (scooped) face of the boulder.
,
pads, possibly a spotter on the rock near the base.
]

Location: Laura Scudder Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Overhanging crimps, slopers and general J Tree goodness.

,
North (slightly overhung) side of boulder. Starts in-between two trees and moves right at half height over one of said trees.
,
Pad (bush will catch you from the top fall)
]

Location: Yabo Roof Area > JBMF Boulders > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Tough hang off a crack with difficult "feet." Big throw and sloper fun to be had provided you can manage the awkward start. Hop on this starless, nameless wonder and enjoy more climbing than you'd expect!

Exit by climbing up and passing through tree branches from the nearby oak.
,
Adjacent to Yabo Roof.
,
Pad
]

Location: Psycho Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
