Start far left with a solid left finger lock and traverse the horizontal crack until you can ascend the wide crack finish. Climb back down and jump off.

,
Flat landing.
]

Location: Triangle Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Up the center on micro holds. Finishes out left from where the overview shows. Worked this one for years. Anyone else done it, probably can count on one hand.
,
Pads
]

Location: Psycho Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Cool moves getting off the ground into the scoop then insecure highball slab to the lip. Traverse left a few feet and mantle over.
,
Good landing.
]

Location: Choc-o-Roach > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb directly up the middle of the face using some nice featured rock.
,
Middle of the east face
,
Pads
]

Location: E. J.  Deluxe Boulder > Lonesome Crowded West > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
A very steep finger crack, in a 45 degree overhang. The crux is probably avoiding the back/head dab on the adjacent rocks. Mostly long reaches between good tips and finger locks. Not overly painful for a JT crack. If not for the jumbled blocks in the landing zone, this would be a super classic crack problem. Probably easier than V6? (consensus should tell us soon enough).
,
This is on the "back" side of the EJ Deluxe boulder. A little tunnel through from EJ puts you under this problem.
,
Bring two pads and a spotter. While never more than 7' off the deck, the landing is pretty bad if you're rolling solo (think Bachar Cracker) and you could easily pop unexpectedly.
]

Location: Little Big Horn Boulder > Little Bighorn Area > Asteroid Belt Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Short Sharp Shock.

Sit start underneath the boulder. Feet up, hands up, reach out to good crimps. Bust out from the underside and make hard pulls on crimps and sidepulls until the incut lip of the boulder is reached.
,
Small East facing patina wall
,
Pad
]

Location: The Wood Block > Love Nest Area > Planet X Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
In your face stemming up a concavity with small edges and crystals for your hands. The technical and precise movements required for success will surely frustrate those accustomed to pulling on holds.
,
Just left of center on the east face.
,
pad
]

Location: Wedge Boulder > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This goes up/down the easy slab on the left side of the East Face. It's about 5.7 with the start being the crux and can be avoided on descent by jumping off.
,
Pad.
]

Location: Cilley Rock > Hall of Horrors Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This climbs the nice, left curving crack.
,
Pad.
]

Location: The Habanero > The Separate Boulders > The Wastelands > Queen Mountain Base > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Work up thin, slick edges to an undercut horizontal crack then traverse right and up past a shelf or go big for the top. Tricky for the grade.
,
Right side of the south face.
,
Several pads to level out the sloping landing, spotter
]

Location: Papa Boulder > Hemingway Boulders > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Works up the thin slab right of the descent crack with thin edges and smears. The aretes on either side are off route.

,
Center of the East Face's right block.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Maverick Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb the arete after pulling onto the wall on good holds.

The holds are positive all the way up, but care needs to be exercised near the top.
,
East arete of South Face.
,
Pads
]

Location: Jimmy Cliff Boulder > Jimmy Cliff Area > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Grab the overhead lip of the boulder and make an awkward mantle to get established at the base of a tall slab which is followed to the top. The top-out it high but fairly easy.

There are some holds below the lip which could be used as a direct start at about V5 or so.Â 

* This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.

,
Left side of the north face and left of Bongo Man.
,
Pad, spotter
]

Location: The Iceberg > The Arctic Circle > Queen Mountain Base > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb up steeper knobs up the arete a few feet left of "Intrusion Face.
,
Pad.
]

Location: The Habanero > The Separate Boulders > The Wastelands > Queen Mountain Base > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Starting from the ground climb up and into an undercut thin crack, getting jams where possible, to a committing reach into the final slot where the crack opens up. Easier moves lead from there to the top.

The landing zone on this looks fairly bad but with careful padding it's actually pretty safe.
,
Left side of the east face.
,
2-3 pads to cover and fill in the rocky landing and several spotters are nice.
]

Location: Puttyface Boulder > Human Sacrifice Cove > The Volcano Area > Virgin Islands Area > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Climb the bulging patina face with glassy slopers and sidepull edges that face the wrong way. Tricky and harder than it looks with a combination of balance and power needed to succeed.Â 

Downclimb off the boulder via the wide crack to the left (V-easy).

,
Located on the backside of the boulder near the right arete.
,

Pad, spotter

]

Location: Tour Boulder One > Tour Boulders > Lechlinski Cracks Area > Virgin Islands Area > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

Center of the North Face.

Location: Pothole Rock > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

Pad

Description:
[
Stand start at a juggy horizontal and work up and right into a shallow crack to finish.

East side of the Hatrack Boulder and just right of Panama.

Pad

West arete of the boulder.

pad

Pad.

Pad
]

pad

pad

[

Right of Holenoid

[

,
Pad
]

Description:
[
Hang start off slopers near the left arete, reach for the three finger "smiley" hold (sidepull) with the right hand, bump to a sloper and then more slopers to the juggy arete. Finish up nice patina jugs just left of Mr. H.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Located on the on the west face of boulder just left of Mr. H.
,
pad
]

Location: Powell Pinch Boulder > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Left leaning arete with a mantle finish. The crux may be moving off of the "pinch" and into mantle position. A great problem to improve your jtree mantle skills.

On the west face of the boulder west of the Molar
,
safe
]

Location: No Name Boulder > Gunsmoke Area > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start with a high left side pull. Pull on and then up to better holds.

Top out with a rounded mantelshelf.

On the west face of the boulder 20 yards west from The Chube.
,
Pads
]

Location: Miledi Rock > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start at an arete and lieback up and into a dish and then work up the face with good hands and smears for the feet to a committing move about midway as you move right into a groove/crack that leads to the top. Descend the low-angled groove on the northwest face to descend.

Rated V3 in the bouldering guide but it's much easier than that, although it has cleaned up considerably since the FA.
,
The narrow northeast face of the spire.
,
Pads, spotter
]

Location: Chocolate Chip > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
The clean slab up the center of this tiny boulder is about 5.9 in difficulty with the hardest moves at the beginning. If only it were taller.
,
pad
]

Location: Intersection Rock > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start up an arete and then follow scoops up the tall face to an easy topout. Head straight back and then right to descend.

About 10' right of the Intersection Traverse's right end up a scooped face.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Wedge Boulder > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
To the left of "N.W. Arete", mantel up and climb edges and friction up the high face.
,
Pad.
]

Location: Mel's Diner Boulder > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start on the right side of the main face and head directly up, using the right arÃªte higher up.
]

Location: Texas Boulder > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located on the face/arete right of Don't Mess with Texas (V1) at a horizontal rail.

Make a few easy moves to the lip and then make a somewhat balancy mantle at the top (a spotter might be a good idea). A sit start is possible and goes at V6.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Piano Rock > Gunsmoke Area > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Friction face, just right of a tree on the West Face and to the left of "Piano Crack".
,
Pad.
]

Location: Picture Perfect Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
It's all in the name. Sidepull sloper leads to more slopers through a rounded topout.Â 
]

Location: Undertaker Boulder > Hemingway Boulders > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Hang start from a flat two-handed jug, run your feet up the steep wall and get in position to reach the arete out right. Once the arete is gained continue up and left to finish with a mantle over a bulge. Fun moves on this problem that despite it's height never feels that bad.

The downclimb is just right of the problem down a ramp.
,
East face of the boulder and right off the trail.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Interceptor Boulder > Asteroid Boulder Area > Asteroid Belt Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start using two good opposing crimp rails and good edges for feet, span up and right toward two thin but solid crimps. Utilizing a good rail under the crimps (easiest beta, but pick your poison *giggity* ) work your feet up until you can mantle onto the slab to your right. Slab stroll to the top!

Established: Nate Pierce
FA: Danny Kommel
,
North face of the Interceptor boulder, to the left of Interceptor(V0).null
,
Pad
]

Location: Supreme Boulder > Real Hidden Valley Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
SDS at a fat flake, reach for a good edge, and then continue up to the horizontal rail. Mantle the rail and then shuffle leftwards to an easy topout. Better than it looks with some fun movement.

Descend off to the right down stacked boulders.

Right side of the West Face.
,
pad, spotter to keep you off the shelf of rock at the base
]

Location: Boulder 1 > Lonely Stones 2 > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

This is the harder of the two V1 on the southern face. Sit start with hands on some side pulls and squeeze hard for a move or two until you get to some good holds. Continue up and right along the arete to the peak following good hand and foot holds along the way or pull over onto the "slab" at any point.

Left side of the south face, just to the right of the slab ramp

,
pad
]

Description:
[
Yabo start at a flake. Figure out the creative start and inch over on crimpy slopers, or are they slopey crimpers? Fun and slabby topout past the low crux moves.

directly behind Yabo Roof.
,
pad
]

Location: Base Layer Boulder > Towers of Uncertainty > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

[
SDS at sloping ledge in center of the east face, climb up more or less the center face on edges, pinches and small jugs to a jtree topout. Fun with variations.

Southeast of Cave Rock and east side of Lava Dome.

,
Pad

[

Sit start from a good ledge. Move up and right following a gently overhanging face with decent edges to a big horn.

Miramontes guide calls this a V3. it's baby soft for the grade

Right edge of the bighorn boulder beneath an overhang of sorts

a pad or 2, spotter for peace of mind to guard from a spiky bush
]

Location: Lynn Hill Memorial Boulder > King Dome Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located on the north face of the boulder at a scooped out area that's about 15' left of Easy Flake (5.7 R), the obvious right-slanting flake system.

Thin, technical edge climbing up a vertical face gain a "lip" of sorts at about 15' where the angle kicks back but the holds don't really get any better. Finish by heading either up and left or right, but beware the direct with it's hollow flakes and creaky edges.
,
pads, spotter
]

Location: Simpleton Rock > King Dome Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb the Simpleton, but instead of following juggy exit right, continue straight up and left a little bit to top out at the very rounded top of the boulder.

Simpleton rock
,
Pads and spotters
]

Location: Fire' or Retire' Boulder > HVCG East > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Delicate steep slab with tiny black nubbins to gain a sloping shelf and then easier moves to the top of the boulder. Best done in the shade and/or colder weather to ensure success on this often tried but seldom done problem.

Center of the boulder's south face.
,
Pad, maybe a spotter

Location: Flight Attendant Rock > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
SDS at some small incut flakes and work up and right into a tough undercling/pinch before moving back left into the regular version of the problem where more sharp edges lead to a long reach/throw for the lip.

On the northeast prow of a small boulder just just east of the sharp Gibbs Arete.
