A pad or two, a spotter is nice for the top section
]

Location: Xenolithic Boulder > Loveland Bouldering > Pinto Basin (aka Eastern Territorries) > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This high quality but heady problem climbs the right side of the immaculate slab around and right of Psyche (V4).

Start from the lowest point where the slab touches the ground and commit to tenuous slab moves on excellent rock that lead up and right past a large ledge and then up the steepening slab above past some questionable holds to an exciting lip encounter 20' up.
,
Right side of the North Face.
,
pads, spotters
]

Location: Family Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Crimp, slap, grope, and wrestle up the arete to a big throw for the top.
,
On the left arete.
,
Pad.
]

Location: Collieherb Boulder > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Immediately left of Herbivore is this thin and balancy slab which utilizes a key left hand crystal pinch midway and gets easier the higher you go.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Just left of Herbivore on the east face of the boulder.
,
Pad; a spotter is nice due to a rock just left of the base.
]

Location: Jimmy Cliff Boulder > Jimmy Cliff Area > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This easier version of Flatface tackles steep thin edges up and left to a prominent rail which gives access to the lip where an easy mantle tops it off.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Left side of the southwest face.
,
pad, spotter (to keep you off a rock at the base)
]

Location: The Hatrack > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Directly behind the Handicapped Parking at Cap Rock is a long, low boulder (The Hatrack) with boulder problems on all sides of it.

This is the left-most problem on the west face of The Hatrack and climbs a pseudo-crack to sloping topout. You'll encounter one good fingerlock but other than that it's all friction and pimping crystals as you stretch for the top - being tall helps on this one. One star out of five.
,
pad
]

Location: Pixie Boulder > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
SDS at the obvious rail and moves up and onto the left side of the slab. Can be done from a standing start which is about V-easy.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Left side of the West Face.
,
pad
]

Location: Sidekick Boulder > Big Brother Boulders > Hall of Horrors Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climbs the featured face/slab right of Squirt (V0). Fairly easy but it might be a good problem for beginners or children.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
10' right of Squirt.
,
pad
]

Location: JBMF Boulder > JBMF Boulders > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Starts from the edge of a shelf with a foot on a small crack and works up and left on the improbable slab via small crimps/crystals for your hands and sloping smears for your feet to a finishing jug.

  • Â A good spot is necessary on this as it has a bad fall potential, especially near the start.Â 
,

West face of the boulder and just around from the Lechlinski Corner.

,

Pad, spotter

]

Location: Hemingway Boulder-1 > Hemingway Boulders > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start with your hands on the arete and your body and feet positioned on to the left side of the arete. Grab the big 3 inch ledge that is in the middle of the route and from their dynamically jump up and grab the jug that is the top of the wall. The mantle is one of the easiest you will find outdoors.
,
the start is a side grab of the arete on the left side of the boulder (depicted in the attached photo.
,
Bouldering Crash Pad
]

Location: Mushroom Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

The description for this problem in the bouldering guide is totally misleading as it's not that grainy, not that hard and not that bad.Â 

Pull into a chimney/slot and climb steep jugs to a chimney move and top out - it's about 5.8 in difficulty. ReverseÂ the problem to descend or jump off.

,

Located on the south side of the boulder.

,
Pad
]

Location: Chocolate Boulder 2 > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start with hands on the large sloping hold at the left end of the face. Keeping low move rightwards onto the face, where small crimpy side-pulls and a sloper allow for better holds on the rail to be reached.

Avoid any of the large holds up on the slab.
,
South face
,
Pads
]

Location: Atlantis Boulder > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Yabo start with hands on the low rail. Work up and right to finish.

Can be done as V1 from a stand start at the 2nd rail.
,
Left side of boulder. Rail is easy to spot.
,
Pads
]

Location: Boulder 3 > Lonely Stones > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start hanging from the arete, move left onto the face then up. The traverse to the left is quite fun, then after a few balancy moves the holds get easy at the top making this fall friendly.

,

Obvious arete on the Northern face of Boulder 3.

,

Pad. Clean fall, no hazards.

]

Location: Split Boulder > King Dome Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
SDS at a flake and then make balancy moves to get establshed on it before moving left to an obvious hueco which is mantled to top out. Can also be done from a standing start (V-easy) by popping for the hueco to start.

Useful as a downclimb as it's the shortest problem on this side of the boulder.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Left side of the left boulder and left of Sakura.
,
Pad
]

Location: Master Boulder > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This traverses up the north-side lip, from left to right.
,
Pad.
]

Location: The Asteroid Boulder > Asteroid Boulder Area > Asteroid Belt Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start as for Peabrain and traverse right or start direct and power over the bulge using the seam/crack to rounded finish.
,
The obvious seam just right of Peabrain.
,
Pads, spotter
]

Location: The Rabbit Warren > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

SDS at a low juggy roof and undercling out into a steep lieback corner, stem left and make some face moves to finish with a mantle onto the shoulder of the boulder and the end of the difficulties. The problem now traverses left for 10-15 feet or so until able to step off the rock - another option is to simply jump off once you reach the slab.

  • Despite getting no stars in the bouldering guide this is one of the better problems for the grade in Joshua Tree with fun and varied movement and fairly good rock.
,
East side of the clump between two large boulders.
,
Pad(s) and/or a spotter
]

Location: Pumping Monzonite Boulder > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Directly across the nature trail from the Pumping Monzonite Boulder is this fun arete problem which makes a good warm-up for the harder problems nearby.

A technical start gives way to fun liebacking up the featured arete and finishes with a committing rockover move up high with slopey hands. Fun moves on good rock, but blowing the topout is not recommended. Two stars out of five.
,
pad
]

Location: Black Lichen Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

SDS at low jugs and hand traverse up and right along a crack then finish up a short face/arete.

* This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.

,
Around and left of Deuce.
,
pad
]

Location: Beak Rock > Echo Rock Boulders > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This climbs the edge of a slightly overhanging, brown, patina plate, then throw for the top and mantel.
,
Pad, spotters.
]

Location: Kranium Bloc > Inner Circle > The Underground > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start low on the center of the face and work up to a crimp and some more rails to an easy mantle.
,
Starts on the obvious low rail. Between Kranium L and Kranium R.
,
Pads
]

Location: French Roast Boulder > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start standing with a sloping left hand sidepull and make a long reach to a sidepull/pinch for the right. Hold that as you work tricky feet up, slap the top and cap it off with an easy mantle.
,
Located on a small block just left (north) of The Hatrack.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Tour Boulder One > Tour Boulders > Lechlinski Cracks Area > Virgin Islands Area > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
The obvious crack that slants left and back right has a tricky section midway and then gets easier. Can be done from a sit start at about the same grade.
,
Located on the east face and visible from the road.
,
pad
]

Location: The Habanero > The Separate Boulders > The Wastelands > Queen Mountain Base > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
SDS at the blunt arete with a left hand edge and right hand pinch and power up to a tricky highstep and then finish up fun face past horizontal slashes. Can be done from a standing start at V0-.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Left side of the west face at a rounded arete and just left of Kiss of Fire.
,
Pad
]

Location: Snack Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Intriquing movement up the faint seam with a nice mantle to finish. The low start is about V0 in difficulty.
,
Right side of the South Face and just right of Morsel.
,
pad
]

Location: Turnbuckle Rock > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climbs a clean slab (5.7) with the crux being the first move which makes it handy as a downclimb. Another good problem to tune in the friction and edging skills.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
East face of the boulder.
,
pad
]

Location: Campfire Circle Boulder > HVCG South > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Starting from the sandy wash grab a large sidepull and sloper and pull up and into a scoop to reach for a distant edge. Reel it in and finish up the flared corner to top it out. An easy downclimb exists on the west side of the boulder just right of the Crystal Arete.
,
East arete of the boulder.
,
pad
]

Location: Forgotten Boulders > Trashcan Rock Area > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This is the short, easy hand crack to the left of Â“LockerÂ’s ChimneyÂ”. There is a hole down low.
Move into the hole then hand jam up.
,
Flat landing. Whatever.
]

Location: Forgotten Boulders > Trashcan Rock Area > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This is the knobby Flake, just left of the hand crack. It doesnÂ’t quite reach the top. Sloper finish.
,
Flat landing. Whatever.
]

Location: Intersection Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
From a standing start get on the rock and mantle up and over.
,
Located on the small boulder to the left of the slabby face.
,
Pads
]

Location: Cap Rock > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Just past White Crack. An easy start to a crack, thin hand jams with crimps to the right and high left, jam a foot LOW and send. Jump off 10 feet to the right.
,
20 feet right of White Crack
,
Pad
]

Location: Big Dike Boulders > Echo Rock Boulders > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This is a fun 5.7 dike about 10 feet west of the wash in front of Echo Rock. Walk off the back side.
,
Pad
]

Location: Chunky Boulder > Chunky Boulder and Trance Stone > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located on the west face of the Chunky Boulder and facing towards the Trance Stone.

Starts from a high sidepull and works just slightly left and then straight up via sloping holds and some edges. The sloping nature of the holds make this best to try in the shade and/or cooler weather.

Not as quality as the left variation (V3) to this problem.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Interceptor Boulder > Asteroid Boulder Area > Asteroid Belt Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This lengthy problem traverses the entire boulder (one orbit) and has a wide variety of climbing throughout it's length.

Perhaps best done clockwise starting from the base of Interceptor - do the start of that problem and then make a low traverse left on slabby edges, around to the backside where the crux span is found and circle back along juggy rails to finish. A little pumpy but lots of rests can be found along the way.
,

Pad (but not really necessary)

]

Location: The Broken Boulder > AFPA Rock Area > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This goes up the center of the face to the right of "Blort". Mantel up to a long reach to the top. Flat landing.
,
Shoes and beer. Chalk and pad optional.
]

Location: Melon Boulder > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
A quick pull on small but incut edges gets you to a sculpted jug after which it's fun climbing up bumps and edges to the top.

Starting off the boulder to the right and traversing in above the crux to finish the same is a fun variation that goes at V-easy.
,
Center of the narrow north face and around and right from Classic Melon.
,
pad
]

Location: Pixie Boulder > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climbs the slabby face using a combination of rounded edges and smears. Easy downclimb off the backside.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Center of the West Face.
,
pad
]

Location: Chocolate Boulder 3 > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
With both hands matched on an incut flake, reach left to the juggy arete, get your feet up and then make some balancy moves (crux) to get established higher. An easy reach, not a throw, will gain a jug, after which easy moves see you to the top. Descend off the back.
,
pad
]

Location: Fidelman Boulder > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This starts several feet left of Fidelman Arete. Climb past three, right-leaning, diagonal slashes and up through a scoop.
,
Pad.
]

Location: The Asteroid Boulder > Asteroid Boulder Area > Asteroid Belt Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This problem is found on the south face of the Asteroid Boulder about 10' right of Ceres and around and left from the thin crack/seam of Peabrain at an obvious left-facing flake.

Match hands on the flake, pull onto a small ledge and then lieback up the flake passing a steep bit with smears for the feet (crux) until possible to grab the top of the flake. From the top of the flake run your feet up the face and finish with an easy mantle.

This problem is unnamed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but given the name Pioneer to honor the first spacecraft to travel through the asteroid belt of our solar system. More inforation about Pioneer here.
,
pad
]

Location: Purina Wall > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
A somewhat contrived problem that starts from a low edge, avoiding the obvious flake for your foot, and then up thin edges to the top. Using the flake for your foot is about V1 or so.

  • Listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide as #284, Unnamed
,
Right side of the wall and right of the yucca at the base.
,
pad
]

Location: The Hatrack > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Directly behind the Handicapped Parking at Cap Rock is a long, low boulder (The Hatrack) with boulder problems on all sides of it.

Right of Turban (V2) on the west face of The Hatrack is where this fun problem is located. Steep friction dishes and sloping edges lead to a delicate finish. One star out of five.
,
pad
]

Location: Campfire Crag Boulder > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This climbs the obvious loose appearing flake on the East Side.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
East Side.
,
Pad
]

Location: Campfire Crag Boulder > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climbs the obvious jagged crack to friction face just left of the blunt arete. Also the downclimb as this is the easiest way up and down the boulder.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Right side of the south face and just right of South Face Center.
,
pad
]

Location: Equine Boulder > Jimmy Cliff Area > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Weave your way up the left side of the near-vertical face following the path of least resistance and enjoy the featured holds. Quality.
,
Left side of the northeast face.
,
pad
]

Location: The Asteroid Boulder > Asteroid Boulder Area > Asteroid Belt Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
You'll find this fun problem on the west face of the Asteroid Boulder between Voyager (V2) on the left and Ceres (5.6) on the right at an obvious left-facing flake system.

Grab a left-facing flake, high-step onto smears and then lieback the flake up and left until possible to reach high to some creaky flakes and top out. This is a fun problem with good movement for the grade (5.8).
,
pad
]

Location: Triangle Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Work up the obvious arete passing a large flat hold before gaining the top where a mantle concludes the problem. It's easier to stay left at the top even though the fall might seem worse.
,
Right side of the south face at the arete.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Chocolate Boulder 1 > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Mantle a large flat hold and reach up for a juggy crack system which is followed to the top (5.7).

  • A sit start can be done and bumps the grade up to about V3.
,
Located on the northeast corner of the boulder, just around from Smoothie.
,
Pad
]

Location: False Hueco Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
There's multiple beta to get across from the start to the sit rest. They're all pretty fun. The crux is getting out of the cave to the rail; you'll have to palm the bulge in the cave and slowly come out and reach. From there, you'll continue as False Hueco Traverse.
,
On False Hueco Boulder.
,
Pad
]

Location: Papa Boulder > Hemingway Boulders > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Hang start off the shelf of The Garden of Eden (V0-) and then hand traverse crimpy edges around the corner left (onto the South Face) to finish up a fat flake just right of a small tree.Â 

  • Can be done by starting directly from the South Face at V0.
,
Left side of the East Face's left block. Shares the start with The Garden of Eden.
,
Pad
]

Location: Jimmy Cliff Boulder > Jimmy Cliff Area > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Footprints climbs a clean slab just left of an arete on nice grey rock with positive edges. This is also the downclimb for the boulder.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Right side of the north face.
,
Pad
]

Location: Flakey Boulder > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This takes a line up the right side of the South Face. Follow the line of broken flakes. Great for getting use to J-Tree choss.
,
Pad.
]

Location: Pixie Boulder > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start and climb straight up on far left of pixie boulder north face (right of 'the womb)
,
Crashpad
]

Location: Piano Rock > Gunsmoke Area > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This is to the right of Piano Crack, and just left of a tree. Climb a Right- facing corner and up right leaning ramp/cracks.
,
Pad.
]

Location: The Pig Sty > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Right hand pinch, left hand sloper, find your feet. Hang and toss for the lip and mantel.
,
Pad
]

Location: Zen Boulder > Trashcan Rock Area > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Sit start and climb the lieback the finger crack.

,

The only climb on the Zen Boulder, North face. Parking lot and back of the restroom is easily visible from here.

,
pad
]

Location: The Chosspile > Gunsmoke Area > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

When the gunsmoke traverse is packed, or you're still too weak and have to build up to it, give this l one a try. Sloper jugs protrude a little more out than the feet, giving you a nice pumpy 20 foot long, but fairly low (safe) way to work your power endurance.

,

10 meters or so left of the gunsmoke traverse. Obvious chalky sloper jugs marks the length of the route

,
optional pad
]

Location: Orange Julius Boulder > HVCG East > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climbs a series of weird scoops in the rock to a sloping but easier topout. Can be started from the left via rounded holds or the right using more positive edges.
,
The obvious groove right of Orange Julius.
,
Pad, spotter
]

Location: Little Biglip > Bighorn Pass Boulders > Queen Mountain Base > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start on the left side of the boulder under the roof at a flat hold. Move up and right along the slanting arete to top out in the middle of the boulder. Powerful.
,
On the north side of the boulder.
,
Pads.
]

Location: Chunky Boulder > Chunky Boulder and Trance Stone > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located on the west face of the Chunky Boulder and facing towards the Trance Stone.

Starts from a high sidepull and works up and left via edges, slopers and hard to see feet under a bulge. The sloping nature of the holds make this best to try in the shade and/or cooler weather.

A more direct version (V2) of this problem exists but is of lesser quality.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Peach Boulder > Fry Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
The problem starts on the left side of the south face and after making the crux balance/friction moves trends up and right via grainy dishes and scoops to a finish atop the broad summit. It's best to be solid on the slab moves up high because this problem is also the downclimb for the boulder.
,
pads, spotters
]

Location: Xenolithic Boulder > Loveland Bouldering > Pinto Basin (aka Eastern Territorries) > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Crank the cruxy start using a variety of holds, past the crystal pinch to finish up on solid patina plates high above the base. Given V0 in the Bouldering Guide but it appears some holds have broken making it slightly more difficult.

  • Listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide as #997, Unnamed.
,
Right side of the West Face.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Mullet Bloc > The Separate Boulders > The Wastelands > Queen Mountain Base > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Up the smooth, swirly slab on dark patina with nice edges. The crux is the first move or so getting established on the slab.
,
The left edge of the north face on the western half of the boulder.
,
pad
]

Location: Saturday Night Live Boulder > Real Hidden Valley Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Make a difficult leg press with small handholds to get started, then work up steep smears to an incut flake and mantle over to finish.
,
Center of the South Face and just left of a small bush.
,
Pad
]

Location: Forgotten Boulders > Trashcan Rock Area > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This is the thin crack behind the picnic table, 75' from the dumpster.
,
Poor landing, pad useful.
]

Location: Manx Boulders - Southeast Face > Manx Boulders > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Step up onto the slab and reach for small scrimps with your left. Make a couple more crimpy moves until possible to move up and over the lip.
,
Right side of the south face
,
Pads
]

Location: Pixie Boulder > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start at the Pixie Slab Right problem and traverse left. Top-out at the left corner. Do the same thing in reverse and top-out at the right corner. Fun stuff!
]

Location: The Pig Sty > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start low at sloping shelf. Bump through slopers to a mantel.Â 
]

Location: Dream Sequence Boulder > Lonely Stones > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Yabo start and climb a plated arÃªte.
,
Pads, has a slightly sloped landing.
]

Location: Teflon Boulder > The Outer Rim > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start on the far left arete on the left most jugs, and work your way over to the right along the horizontal rail that bisects the boulder. Finish up on the right arete (Christina's Problem).
,
Bachar pad
]

Location: Stem Gem Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start at the entrance of the piss crack behind the Stem Gem boulder. Chimney through the crack, as it narrows into an offwidth roof. Pull the roof and finish up the crack commonly used as a descent from Stem Gem.
,
Deep within the belly of the Stem Gem boulder.
,
Pad for the topout. Pants and long sleeves.
]

Location: Pixie Boulder > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
sit start as for "monkey gone to heaven", go left through a low hueco and into a small left facing dihedral, and top out. one hold is a bit loose.
,
flat sandy landing
]

Location: Manx Boulders - Southeast Face > Manx Boulders > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Grab high sloping edges and stand up on a slanting flake to reach an incut patina edge and then wander up easy scoops to the top. Somewhat tall but the hardest moves are at the start.
,
Just left of Right Arete on the south face of the south block.
,
Pad
]

Location: The Pig Sty > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb the left arete on the right half of the split boulder.
,
This boulder is found to the left of the Unnamed V5 boulder. Look for the obvious V-split in the center of the boulder in the backside of the Pig Sty.
,
Single boulder pad.
]

Location: Jump Chump Clump > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start at an obvious right-slanting crack/ramp and lieback/jam/mantle your way over a chest-high bulge to easier ground; the problem get fairly high but the climbing is much easier. An easy descent exisits off the backside.

Not quite a bomb, but the grainy, akward moves may be a deterrent to many - long pants are highly recommended.
,
Center of the south face, right of Jump Chump.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Northern Headstone Boulders > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Also known as Headstone Crack Right, this problem can be done a variety of ways. Good to learn crack climbing, crux is halfway up as it starts to widen.
,
Pad. Single bolt above for TR. Descent is a scramble off to the left.
]

Location: Pacifier and The Nostril > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This climbs an arete with a thin crack on the south side of the left boulder on nice brown patina. There is a smooth face to the right with a hole near the center.
,
There is a boulder at the base. You may want pads and spotters.
]

Location: Fry Boulder > Fry Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This problem climbs a sloping, grainy arete that requires some liebacking, proper body positioning and making use of the power of positive friction. Fairly grainy throughout it's length with some semi-commiting moves with your feet on the very edge of the arete; a foot slip in the wrong spot could skin you alive.

Downclimb the juggy Spud Crack to descend the boulder.

This problem was originally called "Frying Pan".
,
Located on the left arete of the Fry Boulder, about 15' left of the Fry Problem.
,
pad
]

Location: Anvil Boulder > Varnished Wall Boulders > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start on the west face at the obvious arete and work up and then left onto the north side finishing up the arete. Fairly secure moves at the finish but a large rock sits directly under the landing.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Northwest arete of the boulder and right of Forged in Fire.
,
pads, spotters
]

Location: Big Brother Boulder > Big Brother Boulders > Hall of Horrors Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climbs a tall slab with a low crux through a whitish patch of rock and a somewhat scary topout with the loosest holds up high.

Descend the backside and jump off above the Big Brother problem.
,
Right side of Southwest Face.
,
pads, spotter
]

Location: Knuckleball Boulder > Volcano Boulder Area > The Volcano Area > Virgin Islands Area > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Starting from a baseball sized black knob for your right hand work up the sloping arete with technical footwork and balancy movement. Fun moves on gritty rock.
,
Southwest arete of the boulder.
,
pad
]

Location: West Entrance Boulder > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Tackle the gritty slab which gets easier the higher you go. Still a bit crunchy.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
North face of the boulder.
,
pad
]

Location: Penguins Boulder > Jimmy Cliff Area > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Starting from a high crimp in patina and a sidepull around on the arete power up to bigger and better holds and then continue up the easy but tall plated face to the top.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Right edge of the south face and just right of a prominent block at the base.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Snack Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb along the left side of the dark patina patch using good edges to a fun highstep/mantel move to finish. Can be done from a low start at about V0.
,
Center of the South Face.
,
pad
]

Location: Tour Boulder Two > Tour Boulders > Lechlinski Cracks Area > Virgin Islands Area > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Starts on the right side of the face and works up and right on little grey knobs past a grainy, grapefruit-sized knob to gain the arete and a monster jug at the top. Fun problem.
,
Right side of the East Face.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Pothole Rock > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
stand start, mantel over sloping ledge, and top out.
,
Between Pothole Problem #1 and Pothole Mantel #2
,
crashpad
]

Location: Chocolate Chip > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start with hands matched on the sloping lip and traverse left on slopers and edges to gain a juggy rail which is followed left around onto the south face of the boulder (finishes right of the Mini-Slab). Fun moves on this problem that's better than it looks.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
East side of the Chocolate Chip.
,
pad
]

Location: Hoi Polloi Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located around and right from Hoi Polloi on the south end of the boulder at some lumpy jugs and a grainy flake; there's also a whitish colored rock tucked against the boulder just left of the start.

Grab some high holds, pull up into an undercling and make a reach for a sloping dish. Mantle up and top out, heading slightly right to descend.

Some fun moves on this but the rock is a bit abrasive and the hollow holds don't inspire much confidence.
,
pad
]

Location: Arete Boulders > Echo Cove Bouldering > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located on the right boulder and a short distance left of the Left Arete (V0).

Starts from a high pinch and works up the arete/face with balancy moves and creative footwork.
,
pad
]

Location: Seven Grain Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This problem is located on the south face of the boulder and climbs a line slightly right of center up a speckled slab.

Expect balancy movement with smearing for the feet and minimal handholds until about the midpoint where some good edges appear on this typical Josh slabfest.
,
pad
]

Location: Dino's Egg > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located on the northern side of the Dino's Egg Boulder where a large chunk has broken off.

Sit start around and right from the Sit Down Flake (V2) and hand traverse the lip of the boulder around and left to top out as for the Sit Down Flake. The problem isn't especially difficult (5.9) or strenuous and your feet are never more than a few feet above the ground.

  • This obvious but easier problem is not listed in the Joshua Tree bouldering guide but is another fun problem in the area.
,
pad
]

Location: Lizzie Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located on the right side of the west face, just right of Thin Lizzy.

Sit start at a large hole with hands matched and make a long reach for a good edge at the lip of the steeper rock. Continue up the steep slab above on rounded edges to a flat top-out. Despite appearances this has some decent moves on solid holds in a sea of rubble.

Rated V1 in the JT Bouldering guide but it seems a bit easier.
,
pad
]

Location: Black Lichen Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start at an obvious low rail and feet low under a bulge. Work the incut edges up and left to the featured arete making some balancy arete moves before clearing the bulge with your feet. Once atop the starting rail it's a romp to the top. Downclimb the juggy crack just left to descend.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,

Located on the featured arete 5 feet left of Ace.

,
pad
]

Location: Cole Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This goes up the right edge of the Southwest face.
,
Pad.
]

Location: Pothole Rock > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start at Pothole Problem 2 and traverse right through the slopers until you top out at the arete on the far right. Great place to warm up.
,
Start just right of Pothole Problem 1 at Pothole Problem 2.
,
Pad
]

Location: Powers Boulder > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start matched at a high black knob above head height. Use what you can find, and top out.

,
Pad
]

Location: Maverick Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start on low crimps on edge of the small roof, with a foot on the rail. Pull a couple of crimps and join up with renegade.
,
Below renegade
]

Location: Boulder 1 > Lonely Stones 2 > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Yabo (sit) start at the arete with a right hand sidepull and a left hand sloper. Gain a left hand pinch and right hand sidepull (whichever order) before moving left to decent slopers and jugs on the arete. Consider throwing a pad on the impaler yucca! Solid downclimb on front side of boulder.

]

Location: E. J.  Deluxe Boulder > Lonesome Crowded West > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start low on the left side of the wall, move up to a good rail, traverse shortly to a thin hand crack for the topout. Soft for a Josh climb. Great edges

,

Starts on the far left side of the "main face" (the large overhanging wall).

,
pad
]

Location: Powers Boulder > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start with a high right sidepull and climb the gently overhung arete.
,
Pad
]

Location: Crystal Skull > Bighorn Pass Boulders > Queen Mountain Base > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Sit start move off a block moving up and right. "cross" the cave then move up

,

Not on Crystal Skull boulder, but instead on the smaller unnamed boulder with the large cave

]

Location: Family Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start with underclings and dyno to the top.
,
On north face of the Family Boulder.(Opposite family problems; visible from White Rastafarian.)
,
Pad
]

Location: Arete Boulders > Echo Cove Bouldering > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start down low at the base of the arete, make a move to a hueco out on the right face, then work your way up into the stand start with high feet and good body positioning. This adds about 5 or 6 moves to the stand.
,
pad
]

Location: Jerry's Boulder > Planet X Area > Planet X Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start at a thin rail on an eye level bulge, to the right of the center of the Northwest face. Follow thin holds, right, then up better holds to the top.
,
Pads, spotters.
]

Location: Kya's Krag > 49 Palms Oasis Area > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Problem moves up the chiminey between the boulders. It's a little tight but the rock is solid.
,
In between the boulders in the middle. Easy top out and walk off the back.
,
Good shoes.
]

Location: The Phantom Cart > The Outer Rim > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
As the name suggests, climb the right leaning chimney.

Also the easiest way down.
,
Middle of the east face
,
Pads
]

Location: In the Shadow of the Slash Boulder > Western Belt > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
From the good rail hold climb the bulging overhang with a couple of slopers and a high step.
,
Right side of the north west face
,
Pads
]

Location: Cap Rock > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Starting from high patina edges run your feet up the smooth bulge and mantle onto the steep slab above which is followed to the top. Although fairly tall the hard moves on this problem are low enough to make it safe.
,
Between High Heeled Sneakers and White Crack at the highpoint of patina.
,
Pad, spotter
]

Location: Indian Cave Boulder > Indian Wave Boulders > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
The problem climbs the obvious hanging flake on the west side of the boulder.

The hardest part is the start, if you don't use the cheatstone. Once established on the flake follow it to a high but easy mantle onto the top.
,
West face of boulder.
,
Pads and spotters
]

Location: Chip Flakey Boulder > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Make use of the cheatstone(s) to gain the high undercling flake. The crux is making the next move to gain the good holds higher on the flake as the flake wraps back left.
,
50 yards south of the parking.
,
Pads
]

Location: The Asteroid Boulder > Asteroid Boulder Area > Asteroid Belt Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located on the far left side of the west face, just left of Ultraviolet (V2) and immediately right of the walk-off for the boulder.

Start off a small block on the left and grab grainy edges while getting your feet established onto the face. Work up and left for a good hold on the arete, get your feet up and then make a long move to the lip for an incut but hollow rail which is mantled to finish.
,
pad
]

Location: Master Boulder > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This mantels the undercut shelf/flake, in the center of the West Face, then goes up the slab.
,
Pad
]

Location: Chuckawalla Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located on the left side of the Chuckawalla Boulder between Big Lizard in my Backyard (5.8) on the left and Chuckawalla (V1) on the right.

Start with hands wide on opposing sidepulls - left on the arete and right on a good edge - work your feet up and make a long reach to a good incut flake and the top.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree bouldering guide but is an obvious line with good movement on solid patina edges making this another problem worthy of inclusion to a circuit of the area.
,
pad
]

Location: Feudal Boulder > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

SDS at a pinch and a sloper and work your way up the blunt arete using knobs and edges to finish up a crystal slab.

Can also be done from a standing start at about V0-.

  • Â This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Right side of the north face.
,

Pad

]

Location: Hershey Kiss Boulder > HVCG East > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start standing with hands on the obvious sharp arete and lieback your way with interesting and varied movement. A nice problem that requires more finesse than strength.

An easy downclimb exists on the north face of the boulder.

  • Rated V2 in the JT bouldering guide but it seems no more difficult than the problem just to the left.
,
Right side of the west face.
,

Pad

]

Location: Chocolate Boulder 2 > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Starts left of Tush (the flared corner) on the right side of an attractive dark brown face. Grab two high holds and then work up and left onto the face with good edges and interesting body positions; getting established on the face is the crux and is more balancy than powerful. Once establshed good edges lead to a fun topout.

A sit start can be done at around V5/6.
,
pad
]

Location: Campfire Circle Boulder > HVCG South > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Jump for the lip and press it out - nothing fancy on this one. Easy downclimb on the west side of the boulder. An easy downclimb exists on the west side of the boulder just right of the Crystal Arete.
,
Right of center on the north face.
,
pad
]

Location: The Hatrack > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start at a thin flake and reach up and left into an undercling/pinch, then run your feet up high to gain the top where a mantle finishes it off. A little cramped with the boulder behind but the moves are quality.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Right of Porkpie and directly behind the French Roast Boulder.
,
A spotter is nice to keep you away from the boulder behind if necessary.
]

Location: Chocolate Boulder 2 > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
You'll find this gimmie problem just left of Bodacious Rail (V1) on the narrow north face of the boulder. One move, which involves getting your feet established, is the crux (maybe 5.6) - after that it's a juggy slab to the top. Can be done as a sit start at V0- or so.

More useful as a downclimb than an actual boulder problem perhaps.
,
pad
]

Location: Mullet Bloc > The Separate Boulders > The Wastelands > Queen Mountain Base > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start matched from a pointy jug below a smooth bulge and fire up and left to a flat edge before moving back right to finish on incut edges. This is a nice problem on very good rock.
,
Left side of the south face.
,
Pad & maybe a spotter to keep you off the rock directly behind the problem.
]

Location: Creosote Wall > Western Belt > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Grab a high "wafer thin" edge and work up the flakey face past a good horizontal. A little chossy but it will clean up.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Right side of the wall and just left of a small rock at the base.
,
Pad
]

Location: Blip Boulder > Embryo Area > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start back in an alcove and hand traverse the rounded lip from right to left. When you reach the end of the traverse swing around onto the west face and finish up the arete. Fun.
,
South face of the boulder.
,
pad
]

Location: Xenolithic Boulder > Loveland Bouldering > Pinto Basin (aka Eastern Territorries) > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This traversing problem starts just right of Greenhorn Route and traverses the lip of the scooped area to join Enclave and finish up the tall but easy slab of that problem.

Starts low with right hand under the lip and left hand on a sloper or with both hands matched on slopers just above the lip and traverses right using creative footwork and body english to join Enclave. Temperature dependent and somewhat height dependent as well.

Given V5 in the JT Bouldering Guide but it seems much easier than that.
,
Left side of the West Face and just right of Greenhorn Route.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Jimmy Cliff Boulder > Jimmy Cliff Area > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Up the nice grey slab with a a bit of technical footwork at the start then easier moves to the top.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Between Bongo Man and Footprints on the north face.
,
Pad
]

Location: Knuckleball Boulder > Volcano Boulder Area > The Volcano Area > Virgin Islands Area > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start from two black knobs on the left of a scooped and undercut face and work horrible slopers up the steep face to the top.
,
Center of the northwest face and right of Gutterball.
,
pad
]

Location: Mirage Boulder > Western Belt > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Same start as Mirage, but follow the crack left until it ends, then go for the top.
,
Pads.
]

Location: The Pig Sty > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb the right arete of the left half of the split boulder.Â 
,
At the obvious split boulderÂ in the Pig Sty.Â 
]

Location: The Pig Sty > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb the middle of the face of the right half of the split boulder.Â 
,
At the obvious split boulder in the Pig Sty.
]

Location: The Dwarf > Hall of Horrors Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start at the arete and match hands in a thin but fairly positive crack. Small hands and slopers follow. Mantle the bulge to finish it up so you can tell all your friends!
,
Pad
]

Location: The Real Hall of Horrors > Hall of Horrors Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Very smooth, clean splitter/lieback up a slightly overhanging face to a slab above. About 5.9, #726 in the Miramontes guide. Base is being taken over by a Juniper bush though still plenty of space for a pad at the moment.
,
At the western tip of the formation with The Real Hall of Horrors/Walking Mexican Down the Hall, visible along the trail to the LHMFP boulders.
,
Pad
]

Location: Camp Boulder > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start at the horizontal crack used to begin Camp Whore but move right and up. Powerful and reachy.
,
Pad
]

Location: The Broken Boulder > AFPA Rock Area > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start at the lowest shelf, up to the ledge, move left and into a mantle and then finish up the dark brown slab.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Southeast corner of the boulder, just around and left from Blort.
,
pad
]

Location: Manx Boulders - Southeast Face > Manx Boulders > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This is to the right of "South Face". Climb a rib, between two scoops and the arching flake above.
,
Shoes.
]

Location: The Asteroid Boulder > Asteroid Boulder Area > Asteroid Belt Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start from a high LH edge and a RH sidepull, get your feet up and match hands and then it's easy to the top.

Being tall helps on this one as the start is very reachy.
,
Far left side of the west face between Retro and Voyager.
,
pad
]

Location: Chocolate Boulder 2 > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Thin, small crimps lead up the center of the vertical face to join Bodacious Rail (V1) midway along it's traverse right.

The moves are balancy, technical and best done on a cooler day.
,
Center of the west face.
,
pad
]

Location: Dino's Egg > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start with a good right hand hold and make a couple of tricky moves and reach better holds on the slabby arete. Finish easily up leftwards.
,
Right arete of the west face
,
Pads
]

Location: The Doctor Boulder > Jimmy Cliff Area > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start at the right end of the protruding horizontal rail at a good hold. Work up the rail to gain compression on both sloping aretes. Top out using the arete.
,
The route is 10 ft above the desert floor at the south point of Jimmy cliff. Directly above a small wash. The face of the boulder problem faces south.
,
3+ pads
]

Location: Southbound Pachyderm > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Good hand jugs and left foothold to start. Pull up and set the right foot at about waist height, then switch with the left foot, swinging your right foot into the crack, and reach the left hand up to jug. Keep at this level until inching towards the main crack then pull up and scene!

,

Crash pads fit within wedge but avoid vegetation eastward towards the crack

,
2 crash pads are helpful
]

Route: L. Ron Hubbard's Stack of Rocks Mantle
Location: L. Ron Hubbard's Boulder > Black Rock Canyon Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
The reason this is a V0 is because the mantle is slightly difficult due to the overhanging rock above it. After finishing the mantle go off to the right about 5 feet and proceed to top the boulder at the second finish mantle.
,
,
Bouldering Crash mat. for some reason people followed me to this are and started climbing in this area with no protection and were fine due to the low risk of falling, do that at your own risk.
]

Location: Facet Boulder > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Old school V1.

Get established on thin slabby feet on the face to the left of the arete. Make a committing lunge right to the edge of the arete. Find small edges and smears for feet on the slab face, and decent slopers on the arete for hands as you ascend. Make another committing throw/lunge from the steep arete to the lip to top out.

Downclimb Riff Raff or Wannabe
,
To the right of Corner Problem. Start on the lighter tan horizontally curving slab to the right of corner problem and go right to the Arete.
,
A pad or two. The fall is sketchy, but not dangerous.
]

Location: The Chosspile > Gunsmoke Area > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start at the first flaky jug and pull over the bulge with plenty of jugs.Â 

]

Location: Dream Sequence Boulder > Lonely Stones > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start the same as Dream Sequence, but finish straight up the shallow dihedral instead of traversing left.
,
pad
]

Location: Pony Stampede Boulder > Semi-Precious Bouldering > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start with both hands at a good rail and whatever feet you can find. Â Make a single, big move to the lip and top out. Â Shorter people might have an easier time finding feet. Â 
,
On the side of the boulder that faces Hot and Juicy. Â 
,
Pad
]

Location: Sidekick Boulder > Big Brother Boulders > Hall of Horrors Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This is the route between Sidekick and Squirt. Start up the juggy crack of Sidekick (V-easy) and then break right up straight up the face using the sloper and the horns coming out of the crack on the left.
,

These are the two boulders located in the small valley between Hall of Horrors East and West Rocks.

]

Location: Intersection Rock > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start on a side-pull flake and straight up to sloped ledge and then top out.
,
This route faces West and is to the right of Split End Left on Split End Rock.
,
crashpad
]

Location: Crack Boulder > AFPA Rock Area > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Juggy overhang in the bottom leads to a handcrack with a plethora of jugs. Thankfully the crux is getting off the deck.

,

South face of the boudler (i.e. as viewed from the roadside)

,
Pad and spotter. Rocks at the base don't make this a clean fall to the dirt
]

Location: Baby Face Boulder > Western Belt > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start at the middle of the face but stay low in the left leaning crack. Work up the crack then roll out and finish up on the tricky slab.
,
North facing
,
Pad
]

Location: Twin Lieback Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Lieback and mantle, rightmost crack.

,

Right side of the boulder.

,
nice flat landing
]

Location: Dream Sequence Boulder > Lonely Stones > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start, move up to the lip of the overhang, and then left up the shallow groove.
,
pad
]

Location: Crystal Skull > Bighorn Pass Boulders > Queen Mountain Base > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start with an undercling, get over the bulge then follow an easy face to the top. Crux is the starting few moves, but a flying start eliminates the challenge; paste your feet on the nothing crystals below, pull hard on the undercling and send in good style. Not that aesthetic, but a worthy adversary! A truer to the grade Josh V2.

,

East Face of Crystal Skull rock

,
pad
]

Location: Crystal Skull > Bighorn Pass Boulders > Queen Mountain Base > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Sit start off a block. Move up and left following the arete. Easy for the grade unless the large jug up and right is off limits then it's spot on

,

Not on the crystal skull formation, but instead on the smaller unnamed boulder with the large cave

]

Location: Crystal Skull > Bighorn Pass Boulders > Queen Mountain Base > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start on a smooth low horizontal rail. Soft for a V2 in Josh (as the Miramontes guidebook puts it)

,

Far right of the slippery east face of the Crystal Skull boulder

,
pad
]

Location: Smith Rock > Echo Cove Bouldering > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Tricky moves up a left-slanting rail to better holds at the top with the crux at the start where the footholds are poorest.Â 

,
Center of the wall and just left of the right-hand black streak.
,
Pad, spotter
]

Location: Unnamed Boulder 1 > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Really just the exit climbing for the other problems. Reach high for the bottom lip of the shelf, then traverse right until you feel comfortable mantling over.

Yabo start from a low roof to up the grade to V6

,

West-ish side of the boulder. The sloping shelf should stand out

,
pad
]

Location: Psycho Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Three beautiful problems on quality stone.
,
Flat landing with cactus hazards.
]

Location: Two Face Skull > Hemingway Boulders > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start off with palms in the big dish, complete a mantle and then climb straight up to top out.

,

Start in the big crater in the boulder.

,
Mat
]

Location: Boulder 1 > Lonely Stones 2 > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Yabo (sit) start on an incut sidepull. Gain a higher sidepull and some small but decent holds before facing the sloping lip (with decent holds above). Solid downclimb on front side of boulder. Consider throwing a pad on the impaler yucca!

,
a pad
]

Location: The Watchtower > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start on a low sidepull and follow the line shown on the photo for The Watchtower.

,

Joshua Tree / The Underground / The Watchtower

34.0499556,-116.1031417

,
Pad
]

Location: The Watchtower > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start on a low sidepull and follow the line shown on the photo for The Watchtower.

,

Joshua Tree / The Underground / The Watchtower

34.0499556,-116.1031417

]

Location: Yabo Roof Area > JBMF Boulders > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start same as Yabo Roof, then head right through the cave, climbing mostly jugs until the end, where a few stylish handjams lead out the other side. Finishes with a nice (cruxy) elbow cam and a head jam exiting the roof. 12ft or more of pure roof climbing!
,

Location: Pigpen Boulder > Manx Boulders Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
There are plenty of big holds on this testpiece, one of Joshua Tree's hardest, but they can be difficult to use and well spaced at times. An exceptionally powerful and beta intensive line, bring all your core strength for this one!

Starting at the well chalked "tongue" where Pigpen starts, toss rightward straight into a small crimper and an eventual match at the ridiculous bowl underclings, then make a huge move to a sidepull with thumbcatch and apply various foot trickery with more hueco/bowl underclinging to eventually reach down and around to slopers above the lip. Surf the good lip slopers back left to finish on jugs.

Starts in your face and doesn't let up at all until you're out of the sidepull, at which point it relents. A true masterpiece that combines a brilliantly cryptic beta puzzle with raw, sustained body tension and accuracy.

One of the few harder lines here that is relatively skin-friendly. Errata: Toni's last name is incorrectly spelled in the original Miramontes guidebook (new guide is out anyday now!), I have used the correct spelling in this entry.
,
Shares a start with Pigpen and goes through the middle of the bowls/huecos just right of the Pigpen roofcrack, then follows the lip back left on good slopers and jugs.
,
A pad or two.
]

[

Yabo (sit) start at on the left side of the arete with a left hand crimp and a right hand on the arete. Grab a left hand undercling and move to an easy topout.Â 

This is not listed in Miramontes' guidebook, but I'm sure someone's climbed it before me.

]

To the right of First Crack.

Description:

Sit start straddling a bulging arete, making a few bouldery moves out right to some jugs then move up.

NOTE: Feels soft for a typical Josh V3, but I'll respect the author's grade. A much more real V3 is located just to the left, sit starting down on a low jug then making improbable moves up and out on terrible sidepull slopers

Right end of thunder egg on the face which is facing the road

Pad and spotter

Climb the highball crack/slab.

Match on the large hold and mantle over the top.

Location: Almost a Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

From a stand start, use the high dish to perform a challenging mantel directly over the middle of the featureless face. Â

On the south-east face of the boulder. Â Look for the blank side with a high dish and a slightly concave face. Â

Crimp on the horizontal pull up and throw for the obvious hold.

Flat landing.

Location: Thunder Egg Boulder > Boyscout Trailhead Bouldering > Wonderland of Rocks North Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:

Start at the bottom of the Z-shaped crack, moving up to a sloper and edges. Continue straight up (moving left along the crack is the supposed "V5" [maybe in a gym] animal cracker)

West face of Thunder Egg boulder. Climb starts below an obvious Z shaped split in the rock. Right over a boulder

,
pad
]

Location: MP Corner > Boyscout Trailhead Bouldering > Wonderland of Rocks North Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

Start in the lower pair of horizontal handholds in a seam, move up to a 2nd pari, then finally to nice 3rd rail for the topout.

The Miramontes guide says to start on the jug to the right, but it's gonna pull anytime soon, and doesn't really add to the difficulty

,

Sunny side of the boulder (Left as viewed from the road). Starts at an obvious set of horizontals

,
pad
]

Location: Crack a No No Area > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:

Crux is near the ground as you get established and pull on a secure jam but poor feet to make an off hand jam. Eases off as you find a set of horizontals to stand on.

Maybe a pad, but flat and soft landing.

Location: Psycho Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Thin crimps and tough feet make it hard to pull off the ground. Match on a crimpy rail up higher then make a move left to a good dishy hold. Traverse the arÃªte up to the right and finish in a big hole.

Decent landing.
]

Location: Group Site Boulder 5 > Group Campsites Road > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

[

Starts on jugs and you go up the ladder.

far left of the wall

crash pads

Location: Group Site Boulder 5 > Group Campsites Road > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

,
crash pads

Location: Psycho Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

[

Good climbing with tough feet.

Yabo start matched on a blocky hold. Pull up tall for a crimp and work your way up to the mantel top out.

Description:
[

A relatively short slab problem. Feet start on a clear ridge that's easy to stand on. Use bumps and friction to make it to a relatively straightforward top out.Â 

pg 141 Problem 17 in Miramontes 1st ed.

Uphill in between Nixon Cracks and Bachar Boulders. Problem is on the center of the northwest face.

Pad and Spot

Location: Psycho Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Sit down start on a large rail as far left as you can go. Traverse into and then climb overhanging rock to a crack finish.

Flat landing.

To the left of Master Cylinder

Description:

Location: MP Corner > Boyscout Trailhead Bouldering > Wonderland of Rocks North Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:

Start on a pinch on an arete and continue on the arete to the top (don't move out onto the left slab, this is "pinky left". Follow the arete to the triangular pinnacle then turn the lip.

The holds get a little worse higher up, so as you move right, a sloping boulder starts to interfere with the landing and it's too narrow to fit a standard pad on the ground. You can potentially just land on the sloping boulder with the pad held by the spotter so you don't sled down

,

Obvious arete on the shady side (right as viewed from the road) of the boulder

,
pad and spotter (or non standard narrow pad)
]

Location: Psycho Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Shares the same start with the route to the left. Go right to a strange crimp and then to the horizontal.
,
Semi flat landing.
]

Location: Bullet Proof Boulder > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Big reachy moves with huecos.
,
Right side.
,
Flat landing.
]

Location: Psycho Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Match on a nice Â edge Â and finesse yourself up and left to the horizontal then straight up.

Not bad landing.
]

Location: Alisters Cave > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:

Start in the cave at a jug and move out over the roof to the regular start.
,
Pad.

Pads

Overhanging flared cracks lead to an easy but slabby topout. Descend by down-climbing a chimney between the boulders.

Northwest face of the smaller boulder and right of large Juniper.
,
Pads, spotter
