Location: [Redacted] > [Redacted] > Sacred Land > Ryan Campground Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

According to the Joshua Tree bouldering guide "Yabo start and climb the steep diagonal crack, moving right at the lip and manteling over. 7 ft. tall".

Start the same as Painted Savage, but halfway through move up to the top and mantle it. The crux is the mantle but its not that bad. Listed as V2 in the guidebook.

Same boulder as painted savage, obvious overhang line.

Crash Mat

Location: The Wood Block > Love Nest Area > Planet X Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

Left side of the east face and just left of the Woody Problem.

pad

North side of boulder

Pads

Right end of east face

Pads

Pad.

Just right of center of the east face.

Pad.

Right side of the west face.
,
Pad, spotter

Description:
[

Start on the obvious jug. Use a left knob to get your feet on the start hold and then go right to finish the route, or any other beta from this starting hold to top out. V0 is a low estimate for the grade.

Obvious boulder on the plateau in between Chuckwalla and the Voices area.

Mat

Middle of west face
,
Pads

Location: Feudal Boulder > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

This interesting problem offers fun movement on rock that's unfortunately a little on the rough side.

SDS at an good undercling and contort your body (the vassal lean) as you work your hands along the steep arete. Gain a good jug and work up to the top.

  • Â Can be done from a standing start at about V0+.
  • Â This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Left side of the north face.
,

Pad, spotter

]

Location: Hidden Crack Alcove > Shark Fin Area > Virgin Islands Area > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
SDS in a mini right-facing corner with tight fingers and punch it up over the bulge where the crack opens to hands and gradually better feet. Descend by easy downclimbing off the backside then circle back around to the base.

A standing start can be done at a much easier grade (V0 or so); however you climb this the rock is a little rough so tape is not a bad idea,.

  • Incorrectly called Shark's Fin Crack in the latest edition of the JT Bouldering Guide.
,
The obvious north-facing crack in the alcove.
,
Pad, spotter
]

Location: Giant's Table Boulder > Miledi Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start with hands on a good crimp at about 4' From here climb direct up the face passing a couple of slopers on the way.
,
Right end of north easy face
,
Pads and watch the rock behind
]

Location: Picnic Boulder > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Starts left of some black flakes and climbs more or less straight up the face utilizing edges, slopers, crystal pinches and whatever else you can grab. The crux comes about two-thirds of the way up but the climbing is continuous throughout.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
The center of the south (roadside) face of the boulder.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Scum Bag Boulder > Towers of Uncertainty > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

[

,

Pad

]

Location: Parking Lot Boulder > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

The problem climbs an undercut bulge split by a thin crack and demands a lot of effort for such a short problem.Â 

A couple of hard moves at the start gain the better portion of the crack where it opens up, and then easier climbing leads to the top.

,

This short but powerful problem is found just north of the large parking area beneath Cap Rock's south face.

,

Pad

]

Location: The Rosetta Stone > Loveland Bouldering > Pinto Basin (aka Eastern Territorries) > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
If you like desperate highballz, this problem is for you. Climbing is characterized as very insecure liebacking up to hein slopers, finishing with a throw for the lip!!

Same start as Alexandria. Jump to the high rail, move out right into a flaring crack. Lay away the crack, grope the slopes, and bust for the top! The top being about 22 ft.
,
Pads and spotters may be desirable as this problem is DESPERATE!
]

Location: Shipwreck Boulder > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

[
Climb up and left on creaky flakes to join the upper portion of Neoflange and then continue up the easy slab (5.7) above - don't fall as it's a long way down. Easy descent by heading right (west) and down the adjacent boulder.
,
Left side of the Northeast face and just right of Neoflange.
,
pads, spotters
]

Location: Shipwreck Boulder > Turtle Rock Circuit > Real Hidden Valley Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start left of Turboflange and lieback the obvious right-slanting arete (or jump) to high edges that get larger and then turn the lip to finish on the upper slab (5.7) which although easy is quite high off the deck. Easy descent by heading right (west) and down the adjacent boulder.
,
Left side of the northeast face and just left of Turboflange.
,
pads, spotters
]

Location: The Yabo Boulder > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
On the east face. Start at an undercling, move to a vertical patina edge then dyno to the top.
,
Pad.
]

Location: Anvil Boulder > Varnished Wall Boulders > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This alternate stand start to Strength of Steel begins on the other side of the arete by grabbing high crystals and then working up and right, turning the arete and finishing as for Strength of Steel.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Just around and left from Strength of Steel.
,
pad, spotter
]

Description:
[
Located on the north face of the boulder a short ways right of Easy Flake (5.7 R) which is identifiable as a right-slanting flake system.

Start matched from an edge (jump to reach if short), run your feet up and make a reach up and left to a good edge to join Easy Flake. From here you have three options - reverse your moves, jump off, or top out the problem by continuing out right to the west face and paddle up smears to the top.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Uncertain Traverse Boulder > Towers of Uncertainty > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Fun traverse. Another good warm up for Scum Bag.

SDS. Just East of Scum Bag (walk past Scum Bag and on your left). Problem #4 on Shaun's mini-topo.
,
Pad(s)
]

Location: Picnic Boulder > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

This fun line climbs a slightly overhung face from lower right to upper left via incut edges, sidepulls, slopers and some cool moves.Â 

  • The picnic table below the problem has been located away from the base and no longer presents a hazard.

* This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.

,
West face of the boulder near a picnic table.
,
pads, spotters
]

Location: Oak Tree Boulder > Hemingway Boulders > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Sit start at a thick flake and work the sloping arete out right to finish with an undercut mantle. Short but quality.

North Face of the boulder.
,

Pad, maybe a spotter for the mantle finish

]

Location: Pabst Boulder > Western Belt > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
SDS at a low point on the sloping lip and hand traverse, heel hook and shimmy your way to a cruxy topout that's harder than it looks.

North side of the boulder along the lip.

Description:
[
Start low at a jug and hand traverse a thin rail right over an undercut face until it runs out and then mantle over the lip. Despite being a bit short this problem features perfect dark patina and is worth checking out.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.

East face of the boulder.
,
pad

[
This faceted face is on the NE Face and also serves as the down climb. Start off a boulder and move up and left over smooth rock. Bad landing.

Pad.

Location: Picnic Boulder > Indian Cove Campground > Indian Cove Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climbs a just-off vertical face on sharp crimps and rounded slopers with the crux down low and gradually larger holds the higher you get. Just tall enough to keep your attention the whole way and best done when it's cooler or risk wrecking your tips.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.

The left side of the south (roadside) face of the boulder.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Little Rascal Rock > King Dome Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This thin edge problem is found on the rounded southwest arete of the boulder and is hidden from view on the approach.

Start off a flat rock and climb the rounded arete using crisp edges with the crux midway as you make a reach for a good hold and then a jug.

No easy descent is to be had from this boulder - the best option is to place a pad on the northeast face (lowest side) and jump off.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree bouldering guide but is an obvious line with good movement on solid patina edges making this another problem worthy of inclusion to a circuit of the area.
,

Pad, spotter

]

Location: Big Bud Boulder > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This goes up the center of the left-hand side of the North side of the formation. ItÂ’s high and the landing sucks! DonÂ’t fall!
,
Pads, spotters or maybe a top rope.
]

Location: Pacifier and The Nostril > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This is on the boulder up and right of Pacifier. It sits on a ledge, of sorts and has a yucca near-by. On the left side of the Southwest side is a hole which you can fit two or three fingers. Undercling this and head up the smooth face above.

pad

The right arete on the narrow east face.

pad, spotter

Between Jump Nyabinghi and Sun is Shining on the right side of the east face.

pad

Center of the southwest face.

pad

Pad

Center of the west face.

pad

A good spot is recommended on this problem to keep you off a rock directly below the crux.

pad, spotter

Location: Lox Boulder > The Separate Boulders > The Wastelands > Queen Mountain Base > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
SDS at the base of the arete at some incut jugs and surf the overhanging arete up and right to a point where it becomes vertical then finish up easy slab to the top.

A spotter is nice to have for the inverted moves and several rocks at the base.

The southeast arete of the boulder.

pad, spotter

Location: Mullet Bloc > The Separate Boulders > The Wastelands > Queen Mountain Base > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
SDS at a low jug and oooze over the bulge to fingery edges over the lip. Work your feet up and finish up the nice patina slab.
,
Left side of the west face.
,
pad, spotter to keep you off the rock to the left.
]

Location: Equine Boulder > Jimmy Cliff Area > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climb Palomino to the sloping dish then traverse left on a sloping rail with smears for the feet. Match on the far left then move up using a left hand pinch and right hand edge. A little gritty but the moves are enjoyable.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Center of the northeast face.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: White Line Boulder > Human Sacrifice Cove > The Volcano Area > Virgin Islands Area > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Climb the obvious thin white dike that slants left. Thin and delicate with technical footwork.

To descend work down the northwest corner of the boulder and jump off.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
North side of the boulder.
,
pad
]

Location: Modern Ills Boulder > Shark Fin Area > Virgin Islands Area > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

[

,
Left of center on the northwest face.
,
pad
]

Location: Vibrator Boulder > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start at the obvious flake. Pull on the flake, carefully (because it does vibrate), and make a good sequence of moves to get establish on the face.

Finish straight up.
,
North side of Boulder
,
Pads
]

Location: The Habanero > The Separate Boulders > The Wastelands > Queen Mountain Base > Queen Mountain Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Starting from a flake embedded in the ground climb the nice slab past jugs and edges. This is also the best downclimb for the boulder.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Center of the east face.
,
Pad
]

Location: Ladies Helper Boulder > Volcano Boulder Area > The Volcano Area > Virgin Islands Area > Geology Tour Road Bouldering > Queen Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Delicate lieback moves with subtle weight shifts and technical footwork characterize this fun arete that's just high enough to be mildly exciting. The rock is a little on the rough side but the movement is what makes this so good. Descend via an easy slab on the backside of the boulder.
,
Southwest arete of the boulder.
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Gizmo Boulder > Outback Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Start on the right side of the east face at a rounded arete and work sloping holds on both sides of the arete with your hands to gain the top. Good movement on this one with some technical footwork required.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Northeast arete of the boulder.
,
pad
]

Location: Lessons Boulder > Loveland Bouldering > Pinto Basin (aka Eastern Territorries) > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
The main feature on this boulder is a left leaning seam that runs from the ground to the top of the boulder.

Stand start off some good crimps and work your way up the seam.

There is also a possible sit start that has good holds but proves difficult to get out from underneath the boulder, over the bulge and then follow the seam. Sit start probably go at V7+.
,
A good pad and an alert spotter
]

Location: Piano Rock > Gunsmoke Area > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

This obvious slab problem has likely already been FA'd, but I thought I'd put in on MP for those looking to tick something else on Piano Rock. If anyone knows the original name, let me know! 5.8 / V0 problem immediately to climber's left of the downclimb from Piano Rock. Worth taking a lap or two on while in the area.

,

About 30' right of Piano Crack, on the other side of the bush/tree, and immediately to the left of the downclimb.

,
Pad, spotter
]

Location: Piano Rock > Gunsmoke Area > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Pretty fun slab and edging on a taller pillar. While not difficult, a fall could be bad given the ledge below the business.

,

About 35' right of Piano Crack, on the other side of the bush/tree, and immediately to the right of the downclimb.

,
Pads, spotters
]

Location: Lynn Hill Memorial Boulder > King Dome Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located right of Death Spiral on the north face and identifiable as a right-slanting flake system.

A quick pull (5.7) gains the flake which is traversed up and right to a ledge of sorts. From here you have three options - reverse your moves, jump off, or top out the problem by continuing out right to the west face and paddle up smears to the top (scary if climbing at the grade).
,
pad, spotter
]

Location: Snack Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Grab some slopers over the rounded top and press out a standard mantle. Jump off or downclimb off the left side of the South Face.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Left side of the West Face.
,
Pad
]

Location: Scratch-N-Sniff Boulder > Miledi Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
From gritty jugs on the northeast arete work up and right on good edges to a topout near the apex of the north face. Good rock higher on this one.
,
pad
]

Location: Chocolate Boulder 1 > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

Start at the southwest corner of the boulder with both hands matched on a large incut jug (same as for Swinging Richard) and then launch up the rounded arete above. Balancy and sometime reachy moves on this enjoyable problem.

Location: Chocolate Boulder 3 > Chocolate Boulders > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Jump (or if tall just reach) for the twin juggy holds, run your feet up and then make a long reach for another good hold and mantel to finish. Although the moves are few they are enjoyable and worth a visit.

North side of the boulder and just left of Attractive Brunette.

pad

,
Pad

Climb the large flake/crack that runs vertically on the arete.

Location: Hensel Boulder > Scatterbrain Area > HVCG North > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

[

North east arete
,
Pads

Pad

[
A short arete with solid jugs, fun at about 5.8, even if a little grainy.

On the east side (pointing towards Picture Perfect) of an independent boulder just left/east of Leisure World.

Pad

Location: Papa Boulder > Hemingway Boulders > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Begin from a sloping shelf just right of the arete and balance your way up the tricky arete.

pad, spotter

Location: The Real Hall of Horrors > Hall of Horrors Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Traverse to the right, and up, the wall that is across from Walking Mexican Down the Hall. Â Use the obvious lip below the diagonal chimney and the thin footholds on the face of the wall. Â Top out after you pass the large hueco above the chimney. Â The crux is probably the top-out. Â 

You can downclimb by stemming from the top using the opposite wall, or by slithering down the chimney back to the start. Â 

This one gets an R for the potential to pinball off of the opposite wall if the mantel to topÂ out does not go as planned.Â 
,
This climb is directly across from Walking Mexican Down the Hall and goes left to right. Â The start is just beyond the end of Walking Mexican Down the Hall. Â As you enter the Real Hall of Horrors, it will be on the right roughly 35 feet down the hall. Â 
,
Crash pad and a good spotter.
]

Location: The Chosspile > Gunsmoke Area > Barker Dam Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

The traverse right of the Chosspile direct,Â 

]

This climbs the right-side arete on the Northwest Face.

Pad.

Reach high for a two-handed, single pad flat black edge, dab your foot as you reach for a good sloper and then rock up and over the top.

Backside of the boulder.

pad

There are three problems on this face - the left one is V1, the middle one is V2 and the right one is V3. They are all kinda sketchy, so make sure you have some spotters and some pads.

Center of the east face between Mini-Melon and Classic Melon.

pad

Location: Jimmy Cliff Boulder > Jimmy Cliff Area > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Make a difficult highstep/mantle onto the slab where it's undercut and then work up a shallow left-facing corner system to the top. Starting from Give Thanx and traversing left into the corner makes this a fun V-easy problem.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.

Left side of the north face and just right of Struggling Man .
,
Pad

Location: Snack Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Climbs the right-angling ramp system to finish with the last moves of Tidbit (V-easy). This is also the downclimb for the boulder.

Far left side of the South Face and just right of Tidbit.
,
Pad
]

Location: Igneous Boulder > Echo Cove Bouldering > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Sit start at jugs, head up and right into the dihedral tricky or a big move will gain the good hold at top.

Igneous boulder

Crash pad and something thin for protection on a close rock.

Location: Xenolithic Boulder > Loveland Bouldering > Pinto Basin (aka Eastern Territorries) > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This problem is the easiest way up and down this tall boulder and starts with a brief but tricky (for the grade) sequence of liebacks and sloping holds on the arete proper before moving onto a lower-angled slab which steepens at the top.

It can be started from the ground, or if shorter, off a rock at the base at around the same grade (5.7). Nice rock on this one.
,
The Northwest arete of the boulder.
,
pads, spotter

Location: The Broken Boulder > AFPA Rock Area > Quail Springs Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Pad.

Description:
[
To the right of "Marginalia", crimp moves lead to a right arching crack.
,
Pad.

Location: Black Lichen Boulder > Stonehenge Boulders > Stonehenge and Fry Boulders > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located on the north face of the Black Lichen Boulder, about 10' left of Joker (V1).

Pull easily onto the slab using some incut edges, work your feet up and then make the commiting crux moves to highstep out right onto a sloping shelf (5.9); once atop the shelf an easy bit of climbing up the slab leads to the top. Descend by downclimbing the juggy crack just to the left.

Bad fall potential at the crux onto a sloping shelf of rock at the base - for the grade not a problem to be taken lightly.
,
pad, spotters
]

Location: Triangle Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

[

North east arete
,
Pads and spotter
]

Location: Unnamed Boulder > Chunky Boulder and Trance Stone > Roadside Rocks Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Up the slab face starting off the flat ground. The start is a little reach and may require a lunge/creativity.
,
straight back from Chunky boulder
,
pad/spotters
]

Location: Oak Tree Boulder > Hemingway Boulders > Lost Horse Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:

Balance up on small holds to start and then romp up the gradually easier but tall slab. A good problem for beginners or children with a low crux right off the ground and then much easier climbing above.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
Right up the middle of the obvious slab on the east face.
,
pad, spotter

Location: Snack Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Crank crispy edges to a sloping shelf and finish with a tough mantel on this surprisingly technical problem. Probably about 5.9 or so in difficulty.

Left side of the South Face and just right of Dollop.
,
pad

[
Climb awkward moves just to the right of the center of the North Face. It can be climbed either by coming from the seam on the left (V1), or it can be climbed direct with a tricky under cut / side pull at the start at V2.

Pad.

Pads

[

Awkward sit start underneath on steep rock. Move up right, then left on thin flakes. Top out left on slabby face.

Southeast face.
,
Pads.
]

Location: Little Big Horn Boulder > Little Bighorn Area > Asteroid Belt Circuit > Manx/Asteroid Belt Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

pad

Located on the north side of the boulder, around and left from the Flake Dyno (V3).

A quick pull onto the rock (crux) and then up the featured dike system on incut but fragile holds - pull lightly! Downclimb the dike on the south side of the boulder to descend.

pad

Location: The Gumdrop > Echo Rock Boulders > Echo Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California

Start on the left-hand arete, move up the slab above.

Pad.

pad

Dead center of the back of the school boulder (opposite campsite side)

Pad

Description:

Probably the hardest V1 in the lonely stones 2 area. Start at a great jug on the side of a lip with little to no feet. Move straight up on several hidden good holds to easier low angle ground (be careful not to fall though)

This technical slab problem features sloping holds, small crimps and delicate footwork.

,

South face of the boulder with the Iron Door Cave and faces directly towards the Tidal Wave Boulder.

Pad

pad

West arete of the boulder.

Pad

Location: Little Rascal Rock > King Dome Area > Hall of Horrors Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
This thin crack problem is located on the southwest face of the boulder and will be visible on the approach.

Jam and lieback the obvious thin crack to gain a jug and then mantle over the top. The boulder close to the base may be of concern so have an alert spotter.

Note: No easy descent is to be had from this boulder - the best option is to place a pad on the northeast face (lowest side) and jump off.
,

Location: Basketball Jump Boulder > HVCG West > HVCG Bouldering Circuit > Hidden Valley Campground Bouldering > Hidden Valley Area Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[

Start facing the bulge and make a huge leap to the large, but flat, hold. If you manage to hold on get ready for a choss fest as the crystals seem to rain down from every possible surface of the rock. If you are short the crux will be the leap, if you are tall the mantle is tenuous and sketchy.

Difficulty will be very height dependent and will be literally impossible for some short climbers unless they have 2+ feet in vertical jumping ability.

,

Look for the large overhanging bulge on the north face of the boulder. The jug should be obvious about 10 ft up.

,
Pads
]

Route: The Ayatollah of Rock and Rolla
Location: Ayatollah Boulder > Cap Rock Bouldering > Central Joshua Tree Bouldering > *Joshua Tree Bouldering* > Joshua Tree National Park > California
Description:
[
Located in the center of the west face of the boulder, just right of False Ayatollah (V0 R) and directly behind a large creosote bush.

Step off a rock onto the boulder and climb positive edges on good brown rock to a large hold midway and then stem out right to another large hold before finishing up rounded edges in a tan patch of rock at the top. There's an easy descent down and to the right.

  • This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
,
pads, spotters
]

Description:
[
Start at a horizontal shelf with undercut feet and lieback up an offset seam with creative body positioning to a rounded topout. Trickier and better than it looks.

Center of the south face.
